2595 class OpStats(object):
2596   """A holder for statistics about an operator.
2597 
2598   This class holds information about the resource requirements for an op,
2599   including the size of its weight parameters on-disk and how many FLOPS it
2600   requires to execute forward inference.
2601 
2602   If you define a new operation, you can create a function that will return a
2603   set of information about its usage of the CPU and disk space when serialized.
2604   The function itself takes a Graph object that's been set up so you can call
2605   methods like get_tensor_by_name to help calculate the results, and a NodeDef
2606   argument.
2607 
2608   """
2609 
2610   def __init__(self, statistic_type, value=None):
2611     """Sets up the initial placeholders for the statistics."""
2612     self.statistic_type = statistic_type
2613     self.value = value
2614 
2615   @property
2616   def statistic_type(self):
2617     return self._statistic_type
2618 
2619   @statistic_type.setter
2620   def statistic_type(self, statistic_type):
2621     self._statistic_type = statistic_type
2622 
2623   @property
2624   def value(self):
2625     return self._value
2626 
2627   @value.setter
2628   def value(self, value):
2629     self._value = value
2630 
2631   def __iadd__(self, other):
2632     if other.statistic_type != self.statistic_type:
2633       raise ValueError("Can't add an OpStat of type %s to one of %s." %
2634                        (self.statistic_type, other.statistic_type))
2635     if self.value is None:
2636       self.value = other.value
2637     elif other.value is not None:
2638       self._value += other.value
2639     return self
2640 
2641 
2642 _stats_registry = registry.Registry("statistical functions")
2643 
2644 
2645 class RegisterStatistics(object):
2646   """A decorator for registering the statistics function for an op type.
2647 
2648   This decorator can be defined for an op type so that it gives a
2649   report on the resources used by an instance of an operator, in the
2650   form of an OpStats object.
2651 
2652   Well-known types of statistics include these so far:
2653 
2654   - flops: When running a graph, the bulk of the computation happens doing
2655     numerical calculations like matrix multiplications. This type allows a node
2656     to return how many floating-point operations it takes to complete. The
2657     total number of FLOPs for a graph is a good guide to its expected latency.
2658 
2659   You can add your own statistics just by picking a new type string, registering
2660   functions for the ops you care about, and then calling get_stats_for_node_def.
2661 
2662   If a statistic for an op is registered multiple times, a KeyError will be
2663   raised.
2664 
2665   Since the statistics is counted on a per-op basis. It is not suitable for
2666   model parameters (capacity), which is expected to be counted only once, even
2667   if it is shared by multiple ops. (e.g. RNN)
2668 
2669   For example, you can define a new metric called doohickey for a Foo operation
2670   by placing this in your code:
2671 
2672   ```python
2673   @ops.RegisterStatistics("Foo", "doohickey")
2674   def _calc_foo_bojangles(unused_graph, unused_node_def):
2675     return ops.OpStats("doohickey", 20)
2676   ```
2677 
2678   Then in client code you can retrieve the value by making this call:
2679 
2680   ```python
2681   doohickey = ops.get_stats_for_node_def(graph, node_def, "doohickey")
2682   ```
2683 
2684   If the NodeDef is for an op with a registered doohickey function, you'll get
2685   back the calculated amount in doohickey.value, or None if it's not defined.
2686 
2687   """
2688 
2689   def __init__(self, op_type, statistic_type):
2690     """Saves the `op_type` as the `Operation` type."""
2691     if not isinstance(op_type, six.string_types):
2692       raise TypeError("op_type must be a string.")
2693     if "," in op_type:
2694       raise TypeError("op_type must not contain a comma.")
2695     self._op_type = op_type
2696     if not isinstance(statistic_type, six.string_types):
2697       raise TypeError("statistic_type must be a string.")
2698     if "," in statistic_type:
2699       raise TypeError("statistic_type must not contain a comma.")
2700     self._statistic_type = statistic_type
2701 
2702   def __call__(self, f):
2703     """Registers "f" as the statistics function for "op_type"."""
2704     _stats_registry.register(f, self._op_type + "," + self._statistic_type)
2705     return f
2706 
2707 
2708 def get_stats_for_node_def(graph, node, statistic_type):
2709   """Looks up the node's statistics function in the registry and calls it.
2710 
2711   This function takes a Graph object and a NodeDef from a GraphDef, and if
2712   there's an associated statistics method, calls it and returns a result. If no
2713   function has been registered for the particular node type, it returns an empty
2714   statistics object.
2715 
2716   Args:
2717     graph: A Graph object that's been set up with the node's graph.
2718     node: A NodeDef describing the operator.
2719     statistic_type: A string identifying the statistic we're interested in.
2720   Returns:
2721     An OpStats object containing information about resource usage.
2722   """
2723 
2724   try:
2725     stats_func = _stats_registry.lookup(node.op + "," + statistic_type)
2726     result = stats_func(graph, node)
2727   except LookupError:
2728     result = OpStats(statistic_type)
2729   return result
2730

2732 def _name_from_scope_name(name):
2733   """Returns the name of an op given the name of its scope.
2734 
2735   Args:
2736     name: the name of the scope.
2737 
2738   Returns:
2739     the name of the op (equal to scope name minus any trailing slash).
2740   """
2741   return name[:-1] if (name and name[-1] == "/") else name

2744 _MUTATION_LOCK_GROUP = 0
2745 _SESSION_RUN_LOCK_GROUP = 1

2747 @tf_export("Graph")
2748 class Graph(object):
2749   """A TensorFlow computation, represented as a dataflow graph.
2750 
2751   A `Graph` contains a set of
2752   `tf.Operation` objects,
2753   which represent units of computation; and
2754   `tf.Tensor` objects, which represent
2755   the units of data that flow between operations.
2756 
2757   A default `Graph` is always registered, and accessible by calling
2758   `tf.get_default_graph`.
2759   To add an operation to the default graph, simply call one of the functions
2760   that defines a new `Operation`:
2761 
2762   ```python
2763   c = tf.constant(4.0)
2764   assert c.graph is tf.get_default_graph()
2765   ```
2766 
2767   Another typical usage involves the
2768   `tf.Graph.as_default`
2769   context manager, which overrides the current default graph for the
2770   lifetime of the context:
2771 
2772   ```python
2773   g = tf.Graph()
2774   with g.as_default():
2775     # Define operations and tensors in `g`.
2776     c = tf.constant(30.0)
2777     assert c.graph is g
2778   ```
2779 
2780   Important note: This class *is not* thread-safe for graph construction. All
2781   operations should be created from a single thread, or external
2782   synchronization must be provided. Unless otherwise specified, all methods
2783   are not thread-safe.
2784 
2785   A `Graph` instance supports an arbitrary number of "collections"
2786   that are identified by name. For convenience when building a large
2787   graph, collections can store groups of related objects: for
2788   example, the `tf.Variable` uses a collection (named
2789   `tf.GraphKeys.GLOBAL_VARIABLES`) for
2790   all variables that are created during the construction of a graph. The caller
2791   may define additional collections by specifying a new name.
2792   """
2793 
2794   def __init__(self):
2795     """Creates a new, empty Graph."""
2796     # Protects core state that can be returned via public accessors.
2797     # Thread-safety is provided on a best-effort basis to support buggy
2798     # programs, and is not guaranteed by the public `tf.Graph` API.
2799     #
2800     # NOTE(mrry): This does not protect the various stacks. A warning will
2801     # be reported if these are used from multiple threads
2802     self._lock = threading.RLock()
2803     # The group lock synchronizes Session.run calls with methods that create
2804     # and mutate ops (e.g. Graph.create_op()). This synchronization is
2805     # necessary because it's illegal to modify an operation after it's been run.
2806     # The group lock allows any number of threads to mutate ops at the same time
2807     # but if any modification is going on, all Session.run calls have to wait.
2808     # Similarly, if one or more Session.run calls are going on, all mutate ops
2809     # have to wait until all Session.run calls have finished.
2810     self._group_lock = lock_util.GroupLock(num_groups=2)
2811     self._nodes_by_id = dict()  # GUARDED_BY(self._lock)
2812     self._next_id_counter = 0  # GUARDED_BY(self._lock)
2813     self._nodes_by_name = dict()  # GUARDED_BY(self._lock)
2814     self._version = 0  # GUARDED_BY(self._lock)
2815     # Maps a name used in the graph to the next id to use for that name.
2816     self._names_in_use = {}
2817     self._stack_state_is_thread_local = False
2818     self._thread_local = threading.local()
2819     # Functions that will be applied to choose a device if none is specified.
2820     # After switch_to_thread_local(), self._thread_local._device_function_stack
2821     # is used instead.
2822     self._graph_device_function_stack = traceable_stack.TraceableStack()
2823     # Default original_op applied to new ops.
2824     self._default_original_op = None
2825     # Current control flow context. It could be either CondContext or
2826     # WhileContext defined in ops/control_flow_ops.py
2827     self._control_flow_context = None
2828     # A new node will depend of the union of all of the nodes in the stack.
2829     # After switch_to_thread_local(),
2830     # self._thread_local._control_dependencies_stack is used instead.
2831     self._graph_control_dependencies_stack = []
2832     # Arbitrary collections of objects.
2833     self._collections = {}
2834     # The graph-level random seed
2835     self._seed = None
2836     # A dictionary of attributes that should be applied to all ops.
2837     self._attr_scope_map = {}
2838     # A map from op type to the kernel label that should be used.
2839     self._op_to_kernel_label_map = {}
2840     # A map from op type to an alternative op type that should be used when
2841     # computing gradients.
2842     self._gradient_override_map = {}
2843     # True if the graph is considered "finalized".  In that case no
2844     # new operations can be added.
2845     self._finalized = False
2846     # Functions defined in the graph
2847     self._functions = collections.OrderedDict()
2848     # Default GraphDef versions
2849     self._graph_def_versions = versions_pb2.VersionDef(
2850         producer=versions.GRAPH_DEF_VERSION,
2851         min_consumer=versions.GRAPH_DEF_VERSION_MIN_CONSUMER)
2852     self._building_function = False
2853     # Stack of colocate_with ops. After switch_to_thread_local(),
2854     # self._thread_local._colocation_stack is used instead.
2855     self._graph_colocation_stack = traceable_stack.TraceableStack()
2856     # Set of tensors that are dangerous to feed!
2857     self._unfeedable_tensors = set()
2858     # Set of operations that are dangerous to fetch!
2859     self._unfetchable_ops = set()
2860     # A map of tensor handle placeholder to tensor dtype.
2861     self._handle_feeders = {}
2862     # A map from tensor handle to its read op.
2863     self._handle_readers = {}
2864     # A map from tensor handle to its move op.
2865     self._handle_movers = {}
2866     # A map from tensor handle to its delete op.
2867     self._handle_deleters = {}
2868     # Allow optimizers and other objects to pseudo-uniquely key graphs (this key
2869     # will be shared when defining function graphs, for example, so optimizers
2870     # being called inside function definitions behave as if they were seeing the
2871     # actual outside graph).
2872     self._graph_key = "grap-key-%d/" % (uid(),)
2873     # A string with the last reduction method passed to
2874     # losses.compute_weighted_loss(), or None.
2875     self._last_loss_reduction = None
2876     self._container = ""
2877     self._registered_ops = op_def_registry.get_registered_ops()
2878 
2879     # TODO(skyewm): fold as much of the above as possible into the C
2880     # implementation
2881     self._scoped_c_graph = c_api_util.ScopedTFGraph()
2882     # The C API requires all ops to have shape functions. Disable this
2883     # requirement (many custom ops do not have shape functions, and we don't
2884     # want to break these existing cases).
2885     c_api.SetRequireShapeInferenceFns(self._c_graph, False)
2886 
2887   # Note: this method is private because the API of tf.Graph() is public and
2888   # frozen, and this functionality is still not ready for public visibility.
2889   @tf_contextlib.contextmanager
2890   def _variable_creator_scope(self, creator):
2891     # This step makes a copy of the existing stack, and it also initializes
2892     # self._thread_local._variable_creator_stack if it doesn't exist yet.
2893     old = list(self._variable_creator_stack)
2894     self._thread_local._variable_creator_stack.append(creator)  # pylint: disable=protected-access
2895     try:
2896       yield
2897     finally:
2898       self._thread_local._variable_creator_stack = old  # pylint: disable=protected-access
2899 
2900   # Note: this method is private because the API of tf.Graph() is public and
2901   # frozen, and this functionality is still not ready for public visibility.
2902   @property
2903   def _variable_creator_stack(self):
2904     if not hasattr(self._thread_local, "_variable_creator_stack"):
2905       self._thread_local._variable_creator_stack = []  # pylint: disable=protected-access
2906     return list(self._thread_local._variable_creator_stack)  # pylint: disable=protected-access
2907 
2908   @_variable_creator_stack.setter
2909   def _variable_creator_stack(self, variable_creator_stack):
2910     self._thread_local._variable_creator_stack = variable_creator_stack  # pylint: disable=protected-access

2913     """Check if the graph is finalized.
2914

2917     """
2918     if self._finalized:

2921   def _add_op(self, op):
2922     """Adds 'op' to the graph.
2923 
2924     Args:
2925       op: the Operator or Tensor to add.
2926 
2927     Raises:
2928       TypeError: if op is not an Operation or Tensor.
2929       ValueError: if the op.name or op._id are already used.
2930     """
2931     self._check_not_finalized()
2932     if not isinstance(op, (Tensor, Operation)):
2933       raise TypeError("op must be a Tensor or Operation: %s" % op)
2934     with self._lock:
2935       # pylint: disable=protected-access
2936       if op._id in self._nodes_by_id:
2937         raise ValueError("cannot add an op with id %d as it already "
2938                          "exists in the graph" % op._id)
2939       if op.name in self._nodes_by_name:
2940         raise ValueError("cannot add op with name %s as that name "
2941                          "is already used" % op.name)
2942       self._nodes_by_id[op._id] = op
2943       self._nodes_by_name[op.name] = op
2944       self._version = max(self._version, op._id)
2945       # pylint: enable=protected-access
2946

2951     return None

2958     `tf.Graph.graph_def_versions`.
2959 
2960     Returns:
2961        An integer version that increases as ops are added to the graph.
2962     """
2963     if self._finalized:
2964       return self._version
2965 
2966     with self._lock:
2967       return self._version

3002   def finalize(self):
3003     """Finalizes this graph, making it read-only.
3004 
3005     After calling `g.finalize()`, no new operations can be added to
3006     `g`.  This method is used to ensure that no operations are added
3007     to a graph when it is shared between multiple threads, for example
3008     when using a `tf.train.QueueRunner`.
3009     """
3010     self._finalized = True

3012   def _unsafe_unfinalize(self):

3016     especially in a multi-threaded environment.  Unfinalizing a graph
3017     when it is in use by a Session may lead to undefined behavior. Ensure

3038   def _copy_functions_to_graph_def(self, graph_def, starting_bytesize):
3039     """If this graph contains functions, copy them to `graph_def`."""
3040     bytesize = starting_bytesize
3041     for f in self._functions.values():
3042       bytesize += f.definition.ByteSize()
3043       if bytesize >= (1 << 31) or bytesize < 0:
3044         raise ValueError("GraphDef cannot be larger than 2GB.")
3045       graph_def.library.function.extend([f.definition])
3046       if f.grad_func_name:
3047         grad_def = function_pb2.GradientDef()
3048         grad_def.function_name = f.name
3049         grad_def.gradient_func = f.grad_func_name
3050         graph_def.library.gradient.extend([grad_def])
3051 
3052   def _as_graph_def(self, from_version=None, add_shapes=False):
3053     # pylint: disable=line-too-long
3054     """Returns a serialized `GraphDef` representation of this graph.
3055 
3056     The serialized `GraphDef` can be imported into another `Graph`
3057     (using `tf.import_graph_def`) or used with the
3058     [C++ Session API](../../../../api_docs/cc/index.md).
3059 
3060     This method is thread-safe.
3061 
3062     Args:
3063       from_version: Optional.  If this is set, returns a `GraphDef`
3064         containing only the nodes that were added to this graph since
3065         its `version` property had the given value.
3066       add_shapes: If true, adds an "_output_shapes" list attr to each
3067         node with the inferred shapes of each of its outputs.
3068 
3069     Returns:
3070       A tuple containing a
3071       [`GraphDef`](https://www.tensorflow.org/code/tensorflow/core/framework/graph.proto)
3072       protocol buffer, and the version of the graph to which that
3073       `GraphDef` corresponds.
3074 
3075     Raises:
3076       ValueError: If the `graph_def` would be too large.
3077 
3078     """
3079     # pylint: enable=line-too-long
3080     with self._lock:
3081       with c_api_util.tf_buffer() as buf:
3082         c_api.TF_GraphToGraphDef(self._c_graph, buf)
3083         data = c_api.TF_GetBuffer(buf)
3084       graph = graph_pb2.GraphDef()
3085       graph.ParseFromString(compat.as_bytes(data))
3086       # Strip the experimental library field iff it's empty.
3087       if not graph.library.function:
3088         graph.ClearField("library")
3089 
3090       if add_shapes:
3091         for node in graph.node:
3092           op = self._nodes_by_name[node.name]
3093           if op.outputs:
3094             node.attr["_output_shapes"].list.shape.extend(
3095                 [output.get_shape().as_proto() for output in op.outputs])
3096     return graph, self._version
3097 
3098   def as_graph_def(self, from_version=None, add_shapes=False):
3099     # pylint: disable=line-too-long
3100     """Returns a serialized `GraphDef` representation of this graph.
3101 
3102     The serialized `GraphDef` can be imported into another `Graph`
3103     (using `tf.import_graph_def`) or used with the
3104     [C++ Session API](../../api_docs/cc/index.md).
3105 
3106     This method is thread-safe.
3107 
3108     Args:
3109       from_version: Optional.  If this is set, returns a `GraphDef`
3110         containing only the nodes that were added to this graph since
3111         its `version` property had the given value.
3112       add_shapes: If true, adds an "_output_shapes" list attr to each
3113         node with the inferred shapes of each of its outputs.
3114 
3115     Returns:
3116       A
3117       [`GraphDef`](https://www.tensorflow.org/code/tensorflow/core/framework/graph.proto)
3118       protocol buffer.
3119 
3120     Raises:
3121       ValueError: If the `graph_def` would be too large.
3122     """
3123     # pylint: enable=line-too-long
3124     result, _ = self._as_graph_def(from_version, add_shapes)
3125     return result

3147   def _add_function(self, function):
3148     """Adds a function to the graph.
3149 
3150     After the function has been added, you can call to the function by
3151     passing the function name in place of an op name to
3152     `Graph.create_op()`.
3153 
3154     Args:
3155       function: A `_DefinedFunction` object.
3156 
3157 
3158     Raises:
3159       ValueError: if another function is defined with the same name.
3160     """
3161     name = function.name
3162     # Sanity checks on gradient definition.
3163     if (function.grad_func_name is not None) and (function.python_grad_func is
3164                                                   not None):
3165       raise ValueError("Gradient defined twice for function %s" % name)
3166 
3167     # Add function to graph
3168     # pylint: disable=protected-access
3169     # Handle functions created without using the C API. TODO(apassos,skyewm)
3170     # remove this when all functions are generated using the C API by default
3171     # as this will be unnecessary.
3172     if not function._c_func:
3173       serialized = function.definition.SerializeToString()
3174       c_func = c_api.TF_FunctionImportFunctionDef(serialized)
3175       function._c_func = c_api_util.ScopedTFFunction(c_func)
3176     gradient = (function._grad_func._c_func.func if function._grad_func
3177                 else None)
3178     c_api.TF_GraphCopyFunction(self._c_graph, function._c_func.func, gradient)
3179     # pylint: enable=protected-access
3180 
3181     self._functions[compat.as_str(name)] = function
3182 
3183     # Need a new-enough consumer to support the functions we add to the graph.
3184     if self._graph_def_versions.min_consumer < 12:
3185       self._graph_def_versions.min_consumer = 12
3186

3189     """Returns True iff this graph represents a function."""

3192   # Helper functions to create operations.
3193   @deprecated_args(None,
3194                    "Shapes are always computed; don't use the compute_shapes "
3195                    "as it has no effect.", "compute_shapes")
3196   def create_op(
3197       self,
3198       op_type,
3199       inputs,
3200       dtypes,  # pylint: disable=redefined-outer-name
3201       input_types=None,
3202       name=None,
3203       attrs=None,
3204       op_def=None,
3205       compute_shapes=True,
3206       compute_device=True):
3207     """Creates an `Operation` in this graph.
3208 
3209     This is a low-level interface for creating an `Operation`. Most
3210     programs will not call this method directly, and instead use the
3211     Python op constructors, such as `tf.constant()`, which add ops to
3212     the default graph.
3213 
3214     Args:
3215       op_type: The `Operation` type to create. This corresponds to the
3216         `OpDef.name` field for the proto that defines the operation.
3217       inputs: A list of `Tensor` objects that will be inputs to the `Operation`.
3218       dtypes: A list of `DType` objects that will be the types of the tensors
3219         that the operation produces.
3220       input_types: (Optional.) A list of `DType`s that will be the types of
3221         the tensors that the operation consumes. By default, uses the base
3222         `DType` of each input in `inputs`. Operations that expect
3223         reference-typed inputs must specify `input_types` explicitly.
3224       name: (Optional.) A string name for the operation. If not specified, a
3225         name is generated based on `op_type`.
3226       attrs: (Optional.) A dictionary where the key is the attribute name (a
3227         string) and the value is the respective `attr` attribute of the
3228         `NodeDef` proto that will represent the operation (an `AttrValue`
3229         proto).
3230       op_def: (Optional.) The `OpDef` proto that describes the `op_type` that
3231         the operation will have.
3232       compute_shapes: (Optional.) Deprecated. Has no effect (shapes are always
3233         computed).
3234       compute_device: (Optional.) If True, device functions will be executed
3235         to compute the device property of the Operation.
3236 
3237     Raises:
3238       TypeError: if any of the inputs is not a `Tensor`.
3239       ValueError: if colocation conflicts with existing device assignment.
3240 
3241     Returns:
3242       An `Operation` object.
3243     """
3244     del compute_shapes
3245 
3246     self._check_not_finalized()
3247     for idx, a in enumerate(inputs):
3248       if not isinstance(a, Tensor):
3249         raise TypeError("Input #%d is not a tensor: %s" % (idx, a))
3250     if name is None:
3251       name = op_type
3252     # If a names ends with a '/' it is a "name scope" and we use it as-is,
3253     # after removing the trailing '/'.
3254     if name and name[-1] == "/":
3255       name = _name_from_scope_name(name)
3256     else:
3257       name = self.unique_name(name)
3258 
3259     node_def = _NodeDef(op_type, name, device=None, attrs=attrs)
3260 
3261     input_ops = set([t.op for t in inputs])
3262     control_inputs = self._control_dependencies_for_inputs(input_ops)
3263     # _create_op_helper mutates the new Operation. `_mutation_lock` ensures a
3264     # Session.run call cannot occur between creating and mutating the op.
3265     with self._mutation_lock():
3266       ret = Operation(
3267           node_def,
3268           self,
3269           inputs=inputs,
3270           output_types=dtypes,
3271           control_inputs=control_inputs,
3272           input_types=input_types,
3273           original_op=self._default_original_op,
3274           op_def=op_def)
3275       self._create_op_helper(ret, compute_device=compute_device)
3276     return ret
3277 
3278   def _create_op_from_tf_operation(self, c_op, compute_device=True):
3279     """Creates an `Operation` in this graph from the supplied TF_Operation.
3280 
3281     This method is like create_op() except the new Operation is constructed
3282     using `c_op`. The returned Operation will have `c_op` as its _c_op
3283     field. This is used to create Operation objects around TF_Operations created
3284     indirectly by the C API (e.g. by TF_ImportGraphDef, TF_FinishWhile).
3285 
3286     This function does not call Operation._control_flow_post_processing or
3287     Graph._control_dependencies_for_inputs (since the inputs may not be
3288     available yet). The caller is responsible for calling these methods.
3289 
3290     Args:
3291       c_op: a wrapped TF_Operation
3292       compute_device: (Optional.) If True, device functions will be executed
3293         to compute the device property of the Operation.
3294 
3295     Returns:
3296       An `Operation` object.
3297     """
3298     self._check_not_finalized()
3299     ret = Operation(c_op, self)
3300     # If a name_scope was created with ret.name but no nodes were created in it,
3301     # the name will still appear in _names_in_use even though the name hasn't
3302     # been used. This is ok, just leave _names_in_use as-is in this case.
3303     # TODO(skyewm): make the C API guarantee no name conflicts.
3304     name_key = ret.name.lower()
3305     if name_key not in self._names_in_use:
3306       self._names_in_use[name_key] = 1
3307     self._create_op_helper(ret, compute_device=compute_device)
3308     return ret
3309 
3310   def _make_colocation_conflict_message(self, op, colocation_op):
3311     """Return detailed error message about device conflict due to colocation."""
3312     # Example error message:
3313     #   Tried to colocate op 'a' (defined at file1.py:149) having device
3314     #   '/device:GPU:0' with op 'b' (defined at file2:96) which had an
3315     #   incompatible device '/device:CPU:0'.
3316     #
3317     #   No node-device colocations were active during op 'a' creation.
3318     #   Device assignments active during op 'a' creation:
3319     #     with tf.device(/device:GPU:0): file1.py:148>
3320     #
3321     #   Node-device colocations active during op 'b' creation:
3322     #     with tf.colocate_with(a): file2.py:93>
3323     #   Device assignments active during op 'b' creation:
3324     #     with tf.device(/cpu:0): file2.py:94
3325     op_info = error_interpolation.compute_field_dict(op)
3326     coloc_op_info = error_interpolation.compute_field_dict(colocation_op)
3327     msg = ("Tried to colocate op '{op_name}'{op_loc} having device '{op_dev}' "
3328            "with op '{coloc_op_name}'{coloc_op_loc} which had an incompatible "
3329            "device '{coloc_op_dev}'.\n\n{op_summary}\n\n{coloc_op_summary}"
3330            .format(op_name=op.name,
3331                    op_loc=op_info["defined_at"],
3332                    op_dev=op.device,
3333                    op_summary=op_info["devs_and_colocs"],
3334                    coloc_op_name=colocation_op.name,
3335                    coloc_op_loc=coloc_op_info["defined_at"],
3336                    coloc_op_dev=colocation_op.device,
3337                    coloc_op_summary=coloc_op_info["devs_and_colocs"]))
3338     return msg
3339 
3340   def _create_op_helper(self, op, compute_device=True):
3341     """Common logic for creating an op in this graph."""
3342     # Apply any additional attributes requested. Do not overwrite any existing
3343     # attributes.
3344     for key, value in self._attr_scope_map.items():
3345       try:
3346         op.get_attr(key)
3347       except ValueError:
3348         if callable(value):
3349           value = value(op.node_def)
3350           if not isinstance(value, (type(None), attr_value_pb2.AttrValue)):
3351             raise TypeError(
3352                 "Callable for scope map key '%s' must return either None or "
3353                 "an AttrValue protocol buffer; but it returned: %s" % (key,
3354                                                                        value))
3355         if value:
3356           op._set_attr(key, value)  # pylint: disable=protected-access
3357 
3358     # Apply a kernel label if one has been specified for this op type.
3359     try:
3360       kernel_label = self._op_to_kernel_label_map[op.type]
3361       op._set_attr("_kernel",  # pylint: disable=protected-access
3362                    attr_value_pb2.AttrValue(s=compat.as_bytes(kernel_label)))
3363     except KeyError:
3364       pass
3365 
3366     # Apply the overriding op type for gradients if one has been specified for
3367     # this op type.
3368     try:
3369       mapped_op_type = self._gradient_override_map[op.type]
3370       op._set_attr("_gradient_op_type",  # pylint: disable=protected-access
3371                    attr_value_pb2.AttrValue(s=compat.as_bytes(mapped_op_type)))
3372     except KeyError:
3373       pass
3374 
3375     self._record_op_seen_by_control_dependencies(op)
3376 
3377     if compute_device:
3378       self._apply_device_functions(op)
3379 
3380     # Snapshot the colocation stack metadata before we might generate error
3381     # messages using it.  Note that this snapshot depends on the actual stack
3382     # and is independent of the op's _class attribute.
3383     # pylint: disable=protected-access
3384     op._colocation_code_locations = self._snapshot_colocation_stack_metadata()
3385     # pylint: enable=protected-access
3386 
3387     if self._colocation_stack:
3388       all_colocation_groups = []
3389       for colocation_op in self._colocation_stack.peek_objs():
3390         all_colocation_groups.extend(colocation_op.colocation_groups())
3391         if colocation_op.device:
3392           if (op.device and pydev.canonical_name(op.device) !=
3393               pydev.canonical_name(colocation_op.device)):
3394             msg = self._make_colocation_conflict_message(op, colocation_op)
3395             logging.warning(msg)
3396           else:
3397             op._set_device(colocation_op.device)  # pylint: disable=protected-access
3398 
3399       all_colocation_groups = sorted(set(all_colocation_groups))
3400       # pylint: disable=protected-access
3401       op._set_attr("_class", attr_value_pb2.AttrValue(
3402           list=attr_value_pb2.AttrValue.ListValue(s=all_colocation_groups)))
3403       # pylint: enable=protected-access
3404 
3405     # Sets "container" attribute if
3406     # (1) self._container is not None
3407     # (2) "is_stateful" is set in OpDef
3408     # (3) "container" attribute is in OpDef
3409     # (4) "container" attribute is None
3410     if self._container and op.op_def.is_stateful:
3411       try:
3412         container_attr = op.get_attr("container")
3413       except ValueError:
3414         # "container" attribute is not in OpDef
3415         pass
3416       else:
3417         if not container_attr:
3418           op._set_attr("container", attr_value_pb2.AttrValue(  # pylint: disable=protected-access
3419               s=compat.as_bytes(self._container)))
3420 
3421   def _add_new_tf_operations(self, compute_devices=True):
3422     """Creates `Operations` in this graph for any new TF_Operations.
3423 
3424     This is useful for when TF_Operations are indirectly created by the C API
3425     outside of the Operation constructor (e.g. by TF_ImportGraphDef,
3426     TF_FinishWhile). This ensures there are corresponding Operations for all
3427     TF_Operations in the underlying TF_Graph.
3428 
3429     Args:
3430       compute_devices: (Optional.) If True, device functions will be executed
3431         to compute the device properties of each new Operation.
3432 
3433     Returns:
3434       A list of the new `Operation` objects.
3435     """
3436     # Create all Operation objects before accessing their inputs since an op may
3437     # be created before its inputs.
3438     new_ops = [
3439         self._create_op_from_tf_operation(c_op, compute_device=compute_devices)
3440         for c_op in c_api_util.new_tf_operations(self)
3441     ]
3442 
3443     # pylint: disable=protected-access
3444     for op in new_ops:
3445       # Operations created by the C API always retrieve shapes from the C API so
3446       # we preserve the shapes of ops created in import_graph_def (from the
3447       # "_output_shapes" attr of the imported NodeDef).
3448       if not _USE_C_SHAPES:
3449         _set_shape_and_handle_data_for_outputs_c_api(op)
3450       new_control_inputs = self._control_dependencies_for_inputs(op.inputs)
3451       op._add_control_inputs(new_control_inputs)
3452       op._control_flow_post_processing()
3453     # pylint: enable=protected-access
3454 
3455     return new_ops
3456 
3457   def as_graph_element(self, obj, allow_tensor=True, allow_operation=True):
3458     """Returns the object referred to by `obj`, as an `Operation` or `Tensor`.
3459 
3460     This function validates that `obj` represents an element of this
3461     graph, and gives an informative error message if it is not.
3462 
3463     This function is the canonical way to get/validate an object of
3464     one of the allowed types from an external argument reference in the
3465     Session API.
3466 
3467     This method may be called concurrently from multiple threads.
3468 
3469     Args:
3470       obj: A `Tensor`, an `Operation`, or the name of a tensor or operation.
3471         Can also be any object with an `_as_graph_element()` method that returns
3472         a value of one of these types.
3473       allow_tensor: If true, `obj` may refer to a `Tensor`.
3474       allow_operation: If true, `obj` may refer to an `Operation`.
3475 
3476     Returns:
3477       The `Tensor` or `Operation` in the Graph corresponding to `obj`.
3478 
3479     Raises:
3480       TypeError: If `obj` is not a type we support attempting to convert
3481         to types.
3482       ValueError: If `obj` is of an appropriate type but invalid. For
3483         example, an invalid string.
3484       KeyError: If `obj` is not an object in the graph.
3485     """
3486     if self._finalized:
3487       return self._as_graph_element_locked(obj, allow_tensor, allow_operation)
3488 
3489     with self._lock:
3490       return self._as_graph_element_locked(obj, allow_tensor, allow_operation)
3491 
3492   def _as_graph_element_locked(self, obj, allow_tensor, allow_operation):
3493     """See `Graph.as_graph_element()` for details."""
3494     # The vast majority of this function is figuring
3495     # out what an API user might be doing wrong, so
3496     # that we can give helpful error messages.
3497     #
3498     # Ideally, it would be nice to split it up, but we
3499     # need context to generate nice error messages.
3500 
3501     if allow_tensor and allow_operation:
3502       types_str = "Tensor or Operation"
3503     elif allow_tensor:
3504       types_str = "Tensor"
3505     elif allow_operation:
3506       types_str = "Operation"
3507     else:
3508       raise ValueError("allow_tensor and allow_operation can't both be False.")
3509 
3510     temp_obj = _as_graph_element(obj)
3511     if temp_obj is not None:
3512       obj = temp_obj
3513 
3514     # If obj appears to be a name...
3515     if isinstance(obj, compat.bytes_or_text_types):
3516       name = compat.as_str(obj)
3517 
3518       if ":" in name and allow_tensor:
3519         # Looks like a Tensor name and can be a Tensor.
3520         try:
3521           op_name, out_n = name.split(":")
3522           out_n = int(out_n)
3523         except:
3524           raise ValueError("The name %s looks a like a Tensor name, but is "
3525                            "not a valid one. Tensor names must be of the "
3526                            "form \"<op_name>:<output_index>\"." % repr(name))
3527         if op_name in self._nodes_by_name:
3528           op = self._nodes_by_name[op_name]
3529         else:
3530           raise KeyError("The name %s refers to a Tensor which does not "
3531                          "exist. The operation, %s, does not exist in the "
3532                          "graph." % (repr(name), repr(op_name)))
3533         try:
3534           return op.outputs[out_n]
3535         except:
3536           raise KeyError("The name %s refers to a Tensor which does not "
3537                          "exist. The operation, %s, exists but only has "
3538                          "%s outputs." % (repr(name), repr(op_name),
3539                                           len(op.outputs)))
3540 
3541       elif ":" in name and not allow_tensor:
3542         # Looks like a Tensor name but can't be a Tensor.
3543         raise ValueError("Name %s appears to refer to a Tensor, not a %s." %
3544                          (repr(name), types_str))
3545 
3546       elif ":" not in name and allow_operation:
3547         # Looks like an Operation name and can be an Operation.
3548         if name not in self._nodes_by_name:
3549           raise KeyError("The name %s refers to an Operation not in the "
3550                          "graph." % repr(name))
3551         return self._nodes_by_name[name]
3552 
3553       elif ":" not in name and not allow_operation:
3554         # Looks like an Operation name but can't be an Operation.
3555         if name in self._nodes_by_name:
3556           # Yep, it's an Operation name
3557           err_msg = ("The name %s refers to an Operation, not a %s." %
3558                      (repr(name), types_str))
3559         else:
3560           err_msg = ("The name %s looks like an (invalid) Operation name, "
3561                      "not a %s." % (repr(name), types_str))
3562         err_msg += (" Tensor names must be of the form "
3563                     "\"<op_name>:<output_index>\".")
3564         raise ValueError(err_msg)
3565 
3566     elif isinstance(obj, Tensor) and allow_tensor:
3567       # Actually obj is just the object it's referring to.
3568       if obj.graph is not self:
3569         raise ValueError("Tensor %s is not an element of this graph." % obj)
3570       return obj
3571     elif isinstance(obj, Operation) and allow_operation:
3572       # Actually obj is just the object it's referring to.
3573       if obj.graph is not self:
3574         raise ValueError("Operation %s is not an element of this graph." % obj)
3575       return obj
3576     else:
3577       # We give up!
3578       raise TypeError("Can not convert a %s into a %s." % (type(obj).__name__,
3579                                                            types_str))
3580 
3581   def get_operations(self):
3582     """Return the list of operations in the graph.
3583 
3584     You can modify the operations in place, but modifications
3585     to the list such as inserts/delete have no effect on the
3586     list of operations known to the graph.
3587 
3588     This method may be called concurrently from multiple threads.
3589 
3590     Returns:
3591       A list of Operations.
3592     """
3593     if self._finalized:
3594       return list(self._nodes_by_id.values())
3595 
3596     with self._lock:
3597       return list(self._nodes_by_id.values())

3706   def as_default(self):
3707     """Returns a context manager that makes this `Graph` the default graph.
3708 
3709     This method should be used if you want to create multiple graphs
3710     in the same process. For convenience, a global default graph is
3711     provided, and all ops will be added to this graph if you do not
3712     create a new graph explicitly.
3713 
3714     Use this method with the `with` keyword to specify that ops created within
3715     the scope of a block should be added to this graph. In this case, once
3716     the scope of the `with` is exited, the previous default graph is set again
3717     as default. There is a stack, so it's ok to have multiple nested levels
3718     of `as_default` calls.
3719 
3720     The default graph is a property of the current thread. If you
3721     create a new thread, and wish to use the default graph in that
3722     thread, you must explicitly add a `with g.as_default():` in that
3723     thread's function.
3724 
3725     The following code examples are equivalent:
3726 
3727     ```python
3728     # 1. Using Graph.as_default():
3729     g = tf.Graph()
3730     with g.as_default():
3731       c = tf.constant(5.0)
3732       assert c.graph is g
3733 
3734     # 2. Constructing and making default:
3735     with tf.Graph().as_default() as g:
3736       c = tf.constant(5.0)
3737       assert c.graph is g
3738     ```
3739 
3740     If eager execution is enabled ops created under this context manager will be
3741     added to the graph instead of executed eagerly.
3742 
3743     Returns:
3744       A context manager for using this graph as the default graph.
3745     """
3746     return _default_graph_stack.get_controller(self)

3748   @property
3749   def collections(self):
3750     """Returns the names of the collections known to this graph."""

3753   def add_to_collection(self, name, value):
3754     """Stores `value` in the collection with the given `name`.
3755 
3756     Note that collections are not sets, so it is possible to add a value to
3757     a collection several times.
3758 
3759     Args:
3760       name: The key for the collection. The `GraphKeys` class
3761         contains many standard names for collections.
3762       value: The value to add to the collection.
3763     """  # pylint: disable=g-doc-exception
3764     self._check_not_finalized()
3765     with self._lock:
3766       if name not in self._collections:
3767         self._collections[name] = [value]
3768       else:
3769         self._collections[name].append(value)
3770 
3771   def add_to_collections(self, names, value):
3772     """Stores `value` in the collections given by `names`.
3773 
3774     Note that collections are not sets, so it is possible to add a value to
3775     a collection several times. This function makes sure that duplicates in
3776     `names` are ignored, but it will not check for pre-existing membership of
3777     `value` in any of the collections in `names`.
3778 
3779     `names` can be any iterable, but if `names` is a string, it is treated as a
3780     single collection name.
3781 
3782     Args:
3783       names: The keys for the collections to add to. The `GraphKeys` class
3784         contains many standard names for collections.
3785       value: The value to add to the collections.
3786     """
3787     # Make sure names are unique, but treat strings as a single collection name
3788     names = (names,) if isinstance(names, six.string_types) else set(names)
3789     for name in names:
3790       self.add_to_collection(name, value)
3791 
3792   def get_collection_ref(self, name):
3793     """Returns a list of values in the collection with the given `name`.
3794 
3795     If the collection exists, this returns the list itself, which can
3796     be modified in place to change the collection.  If the collection does
3797     not exist, it is created as an empty list and the list is returned.
3798 
3799     This is different from `get_collection()` which always returns a copy of
3800     the collection list if it exists and never creates an empty collection.
3801 
3802     Args:
3803       name: The key for the collection. For example, the `GraphKeys` class
3804         contains many standard names for collections.
3805 
3806     Returns:
3807       The list of values in the collection with the given `name`, or an empty
3808       list if no value has been added to that collection.
3809     """  # pylint: disable=g-doc-exception
3810     with self._lock:
3811       coll_list = self._collections.get(name, None)
3812       if coll_list is None:
3813         coll_list = []
3814         self._collections[name] = coll_list
3815       return coll_list
3816 
3817   def get_collection(self, name, scope=None):
3818     """Returns a list of values in the collection with the given `name`.
3819 
3820     This is different from `get_collection_ref()` which always returns the
3821     actual collection list if it exists in that it returns a new list each time
3822     it is called.
3823 
3824     Args:
3825       name: The key for the collection. For example, the `GraphKeys` class
3826         contains many standard names for collections.
3827       scope: (Optional.) A string. If supplied, the resulting list is filtered
3828         to include only items whose `name` attribute matches `scope` using
3829         `re.match`. Items without a `name` attribute are never returned if a
3830         scope is supplied. The choice of `re.match` means that a `scope` without
3831         special tokens filters by prefix.
3832 
3833     Returns:
3834       The list of values in the collection with the given `name`, or
3835       an empty list if no value has been added to that collection. The
3836       list contains the values in the order under which they were
3837       collected.
3838     """  # pylint: disable=g-doc-exception
3839     with self._lock:
3840       collection = self._collections.get(name, None)
3841       if collection is None:
3842         return []
3843       if scope is None:
3844         return list(collection)
3845       else:
3846         c = []
3847         regex = re.compile(scope)
3848         for item in collection:
3849           if hasattr(item, "name") and regex.match(item.name):
3850             c.append(item)
3851         return c
3852 
3853   def get_all_collection_keys(self):
3854     """Returns a list of collections used in this graph."""
3855     with self._lock:
3856       return [x for x in self._collections if isinstance(x, six.string_types)]
3857 
3858   def clear_collection(self, name):
3859     """Clears all values in a collection.
3860 
3861     Args:
3862       name: The key for the collection. The `GraphKeys` class contains many
3863         standard names for collections.
3864     """
3865     self._check_not_finalized()
3866     with self._lock:
3867       if name in self._collections:
3868         del self._collections[name]

3870   @tf_contextlib.contextmanager
3871   def _original_op(self, op):
3872     """Python 'with' handler to help annotate ops with their originator.
3873 
3874     An op may have an 'original_op' property that indicates the op on which
3875     it was based. For example a replica op is based on the op that was
3876     replicated and a gradient op is based on the op that was differentiated.
3877 
3878     All ops created in the scope of this 'with' handler will have
3879     the given 'op' as their original op.
3880 
3881     Args:
3882       op: The Operation that all ops created in this scope will have as their
3883         original op.
3884 
3885     Yields:
3886       Nothing.
3887     """
3888     old_original_op = self._default_original_op
3889     self._default_original_op = op
3890     try:
3891       yield
3892     finally:
3893       self._default_original_op = old_original_op

3895   @property

3898     if not hasattr(self._thread_local, "_name_stack"):
3899       self._thread_local._name_stack = ""
3900     return self._thread_local._name_stack
