3906   # pylint: disable=g-doc-return-or-yield,line-too-long
3907   @tf_contextlib.contextmanager
3908   def name_scope(self, name):
3909     r"""Returns a context manager that creates hierarchical names for operations.
3910 
3911     A graph maintains a stack of name scopes. A `with name_scope(...):`
3912     statement pushes a new name onto the stack for the lifetime of the context.
3913 
3914     The `name` argument will be interpreted as follows:
3915 
3916     * A string (not ending with '/') will create a new name scope, in which
3917       `name` is appended to the prefix of all operations created in the
3918       context. If `name` has been used before, it will be made unique by
3919       calling `self.unique_name(name)`.
3920     * A scope previously captured from a `with g.name_scope(...) as
3921       scope:` statement will be treated as an "absolute" name scope, which
3922       makes it possible to re-enter existing scopes.
3923     * A value of `None` or the empty string will reset the current name scope
3924       to the top-level (empty) name scope.
3925 
3926     For example:
3927 
3928     ```python
3929     with tf.Graph().as_default() as g:
3930       c = tf.constant(5.0, name="c")
3931       assert c.op.name == "c"
3932       c_1 = tf.constant(6.0, name="c")
3933       assert c_1.op.name == "c_1"
3934 
3935       # Creates a scope called "nested"
3936       with g.name_scope("nested") as scope:
3937         nested_c = tf.constant(10.0, name="c")
3938         assert nested_c.op.name == "nested/c"
3939 
3940         # Creates a nested scope called "inner".
3941         with g.name_scope("inner"):
3942           nested_inner_c = tf.constant(20.0, name="c")
3943           assert nested_inner_c.op.name == "nested/inner/c"
3944 
3945         # Create a nested scope called "inner_1".
3946         with g.name_scope("inner"):
3947           nested_inner_1_c = tf.constant(30.0, name="c")
3948           assert nested_inner_1_c.op.name == "nested/inner_1/c"
3949 
3950           # Treats `scope` as an absolute name scope, and
3951           # switches to the "nested/" scope.
3952           with g.name_scope(scope):
3953             nested_d = tf.constant(40.0, name="d")
3954             assert nested_d.op.name == "nested/d"
3955 
3956             with g.name_scope(""):
3957               e = tf.constant(50.0, name="e")
3958               assert e.op.name == "e"
3959     ```
3960 
3961     The name of the scope itself can be captured by `with
3962     g.name_scope(...) as scope:`, which stores the name of the scope
3963     in the variable `scope`. This value can be used to name an
3964     operation that represents the overall result of executing the ops
3965     in a scope. For example:
3966 
3967     ```python
3968     inputs = tf.constant(...)
3969     with g.name_scope('my_layer') as scope:
3970       weights = tf.Variable(..., name="weights")
3971       biases = tf.Variable(..., name="biases")
3972       affine = tf.matmul(inputs, weights) + biases
3973       output = tf.nn.relu(affine, name=scope)
3974     ```
3975 
3976     NOTE: This constructor validates the given `name`. Valid scope
3977     names match one of the following regular expressions:
3978 
3979         [A-Za-z0-9.][A-Za-z0-9_.\\-/]* (for scopes at the root)
3980         [A-Za-z0-9_.\\-/]* (for other scopes)
3981 
3982     Args:
3983       name: A name for the scope.
3984 
3985     Returns:
3986       A context manager that installs `name` as a new name scope.
3987 
3988     Raises:
3989       ValueError: If `name` is not a valid scope name, according to the rules
3990         above.
3991     """
3992     if name:
3993       if isinstance(name, compat.bytes_or_text_types):
3994         name = compat.as_str(name)
3995 
3996       if self._name_stack:
3997         # Scopes created in a nested scope may have initial characters
3998         # that are illegal as the initial character of an op name
3999         # (viz. '-', '\', '/', and '_').
4000         if not _VALID_SCOPE_NAME_REGEX.match(name):
4001           raise ValueError("'%s' is not a valid scope name" % name)
4002       else:
4003         # Scopes created in the root must match the more restrictive
4004         # op name regex, which constrains the initial character.
4005         if not _VALID_OP_NAME_REGEX.match(name):
4006           raise ValueError("'%s' is not a valid scope name" % name)
4007     old_stack = self._name_stack
4008     if not name:  # Both for name=None and name="" we re-set to empty scope.
4009       new_stack = None
4010     elif name[-1] == "/":
4011       new_stack = _name_from_scope_name(name)
4012     else:
4013       new_stack = self.unique_name(name)
4014     self._name_stack = new_stack
4015     try:
4016       yield "" if new_stack is None else new_stack + "/"
4017     finally:
4018       self._name_stack = old_stack
4019 
4020   # pylint: enable=g-doc-return-or-yield,line-too-long
4021 
4022   def unique_name(self, name, mark_as_used=True):
4023     """Return a unique operation name for `name`.
4024 
4025     Note: You rarely need to call `unique_name()` directly.  Most of
4026     the time you just need to create `with g.name_scope()` blocks to
4027     generate structured names.
4028 
4029     `unique_name` is used to generate structured names, separated by
4030     `"/"`, to help identify operations when debugging a graph.
4031     Operation names are displayed in error messages reported by the
4032     TensorFlow runtime, and in various visualization tools such as
4033     TensorBoard.
4034 
4035     If `mark_as_used` is set to `True`, which is the default, a new
4036     unique name is created and marked as in use. If it's set to `False`,
4037     the unique name is returned without actually being marked as used.
4038     This is useful when the caller simply wants to know what the name
4039     to be created will be.
4040 
4041     Args:
4042       name: The name for an operation.
4043       mark_as_used: Whether to mark this name as being used.
4044 
4045     Returns:
4046       A string to be passed to `create_op()` that will be used
4047       to name the operation being created.
4048     """
4049     if self._name_stack:
4050       name = self._name_stack + "/" + name
4051 
4052     # For the sake of checking for names in use, we treat names as case
4053     # insensitive (e.g. foo = Foo).
4054     name_key = name.lower()
4055     i = self._names_in_use.get(name_key, 0)
4056     # Increment the number for "name_key".
4057     if mark_as_used:
4058       self._names_in_use[name_key] = i + 1
4059     if i > 0:
4060       base_name_key = name_key
4061       # Make sure the composed name key is not already used.
4062       while name_key in self._names_in_use:
4063         name_key = "%s_%d" % (base_name_key, i)
4064         i += 1
4065       # Mark the composed name_key as used in case someone wants
4066       # to call unique_name("name_1").
4067       if mark_as_used:
4068         self._names_in_use[name_key] = 1
4069 
4070       # Return the new name with the original capitalization of the given name.
4071       name = "%s_%d" % (name, i-1)
4072     return name
4073 
4074   def get_name_scope(self):
4075     """Returns the current name scope.
4076 
4077     For example:
4078 
4079     ```python
4080     with tf.name_scope('scope1'):
4081       with tf.name_scope('scope2'):
4082         print(tf.get_default_graph().get_name_scope())
4083     ```
4084     would print the string `scope1/scope2`.
4085 
4086     Returns:
4087       A string representing the current name scope.
4088     """
4089     return self._name_stack
4090 
4091   @tf_contextlib.contextmanager
4092   def _colocate_with_for_gradient(self, op, gradient_uid,
4093                                   ignore_existing=False):
4094     with self.colocate_with(op, ignore_existing):
4095       if gradient_uid is not None and self._control_flow_context is not None:
4096         self._control_flow_context.EnterGradientColocation(op, gradient_uid)
4097         try:
4098           yield
4099         finally:
4100           self._control_flow_context.ExitGradientColocation(op, gradient_uid)
4101       else:
4102         yield
4103 
4104   @tf_contextlib.contextmanager
4105   def colocate_with(self, op, ignore_existing=False):
4106     """Returns a context manager that specifies an op to colocate with.
4107 
4108     Note: this function is not for public use, only for internal libraries.
4109 
4110     For example:
4111 
4112     ```python
4113     a = tf.Variable([1.0])
4114     with g.colocate_with(a):
4115       b = tf.constant(1.0)
4116       c = tf.add(a, b)
4117     ```
4118 
4119     `b` and `c` will always be colocated with `a`, no matter where `a`
4120     is eventually placed.
4121 
4122     **NOTE** Using a colocation scope resets any existing device constraints.
4123 
4124     If `op` is `None` then `ignore_existing` must be `True` and the new
4125     scope resets all colocation and device constraints.
4126 
4127     Args:
4128       op: The op to colocate all created ops with, or `None`.
4129       ignore_existing: If true, only applies colocation of this op within
4130         the context, rather than applying all colocation properties
4131         on the stack.  If `op` is `None`, this value must be `True`.
4132 
4133     Raises:
4134       ValueError: if op is None but ignore_existing is False.
4135 
4136     Yields:
4137       A context manager that specifies the op with which to colocate
4138       newly created ops.
4139     """
4140     if op is None and not ignore_existing:
4141       raise ValueError("Trying to reset colocation (op is None) but "
4142                        "ignore_existing is not True")
4143 
4144     if op is not None and not isinstance(op, Operation):
4145       # We always want to colocate with the reference op.
4146       op = internal_convert_to_tensor_or_indexed_slices(op, as_ref=True).op
4147 
4148     # By default, colocate_with resets the device function stack,
4149     # since colocate_with is typically used in specific internal
4150     # library functions where colocation is intended to be "stronger"
4151     # than device functions.
4152     #
4153     # In the future, a caller may specify that device_functions win
4154     # over colocation, in which case we can add support.
4155     device_fn_tmp = self._device_function_stack
4156     self._device_function_stack = traceable_stack.TraceableStack()
4157 
4158     if ignore_existing:
4159       current_stack = self._colocation_stack
4160       self._colocation_stack = traceable_stack.TraceableStack()
4161 
4162     if op is not None:
4163       # offset refers to the stack frame used for storing code location.
4164       # We use 4, the sum of 1 to use our caller's stack frame and 3
4165       # to jump over layers of context managers above us.
4166       self._colocation_stack.push_obj(op, offset=4)
4167 
4168     try:
4169       yield
4170     finally:
4171       # Restore device function stack
4172       self._device_function_stack = device_fn_tmp
4173       if op is not None:
4174         self._colocation_stack.pop_obj()
4175 
4176       # Reset the colocation stack if requested.
4177       if ignore_existing:
4178         self._colocation_stack = current_stack
4179 
4180   def _add_device_to_stack(self, device_name_or_function, offset=0):
4181     """Add device to stack manually, separate from a context manager."""
4182     total_offset = 1 + offset
4183     spec = _UserDeviceSpec(device_name_or_function)
4184     self._device_function_stack.push_obj(spec, offset=total_offset)
4185     return spec
4186 
4187   @tf_contextlib.contextmanager
4188   def device(self, device_name_or_function):
4189     # pylint: disable=line-too-long
4190     """Returns a context manager that specifies the default device to use.
4191 
4192     The `device_name_or_function` argument may either be a device name
4193     string, a device function, or None:
4194 
4195     * If it is a device name string, all operations constructed in
4196       this context will be assigned to the device with that name, unless
4197       overridden by a nested `device()` context.
4198     * If it is a function, it will be treated as a function from
4199       Operation objects to device name strings, and invoked each time
4200       a new Operation is created. The Operation will be assigned to
4201       the device with the returned name.
4202     * If it is None, all `device()` invocations from the enclosing context
4203       will be ignored.
4204 
4205     For information about the valid syntax of device name strings, see
4206     the documentation in
4207     [`DeviceNameUtils`](https://www.tensorflow.org/code/tensorflow/core/util/device_name_utils.h).
4208 
4209     For example:
4210 
4211     ```python
4212     with g.device('/device:GPU:0'):
4213       # All operations constructed in this context will be placed
4214       # on GPU 0.
4215       with g.device(None):
4216         # All operations constructed in this context will have no
4217         # assigned device.
4218 
4219     # Defines a function from `Operation` to device string.
4220     def matmul_on_gpu(n):
4221       if n.type == "MatMul":
4222         return "/device:GPU:0"
4223       else:
4224         return "/cpu:0"
4225 
4226     with g.device(matmul_on_gpu):
4227       # All operations of type "MatMul" constructed in this context
4228       # will be placed on GPU 0; all other operations will be placed
4229       # on CPU 0.
4230     ```
4231 
4232     **N.B.** The device scope may be overridden by op wrappers or
4233     other library code. For example, a variable assignment op
4234     `v.assign()` must be colocated with the `tf.Variable` `v`, and
4235     incompatible device scopes will be ignored.
4236 
4237     Args:
4238       device_name_or_function: The device name or function to use in
4239         the context.
4240 
4241     Yields:
4242       A context manager that specifies the default device to use for newly
4243       created ops.
4244     """
4245     self._add_device_to_stack(device_name_or_function, offset=2)
4246     try:
4247       yield
4248     finally:
4249       self._device_function_stack.pop_obj()
4250 
4251   def _apply_device_functions(self, op):
4252     """Applies the current device function stack to the given operation."""
4253     # Apply any device functions in LIFO order, so that the most recently
4254     # pushed function has the first chance to apply a device to the op.
4255     # We apply here because the result can depend on the Operation's
4256     # signature, which is computed in the Operation constructor.
4257     # pylint: disable=protected-access
4258     for device_spec in self._device_function_stack.peek_objs():
4259       if device_spec.function is None:
4260         break
4261       op._set_device(device_spec.function(op))
4262     op._device_code_locations = self._snapshot_device_function_stack_metadata()
4263     # pylint: enable=protected-access
4264 
4265   # pylint: disable=g-doc-return-or-yield
4266   @tf_contextlib.contextmanager
4267   def container(self, container_name):
4268     """Returns a context manager that specifies the resource container to use.
4269 
4270     Stateful operations, such as variables and queues, can maintain their
4271     states on devices so that they can be shared by multiple processes.
4272     A resource container is a string name under which these stateful
4273     operations are tracked. These resources can be released or cleared
4274     with `tf.Session.reset()`.
4275 
4276     For example:
4277 
4278     ```python
4279     with g.container('experiment0'):
4280       # All stateful Operations constructed in this context will be placed
4281       # in resource container "experiment0".
4282       v1 = tf.Variable([1.0])
4283       v2 = tf.Variable([2.0])
4284       with g.container("experiment1"):
4285         # All stateful Operations constructed in this context will be
4286         # placed in resource container "experiment1".
4287         v3 = tf.Variable([3.0])
4288         q1 = tf.FIFOQueue(10, tf.float32)
4289       # All stateful Operations constructed in this context will be
4290       # be created in the "experiment0".
4291       v4 = tf.Variable([4.0])
4292       q1 = tf.FIFOQueue(20, tf.float32)
4293       with g.container(""):
4294         # All stateful Operations constructed in this context will be
4295         # be placed in the default resource container.
4296         v5 = tf.Variable([5.0])
4297         q3 = tf.FIFOQueue(30, tf.float32)
4298 
4299     # Resets container "experiment0", after which the state of v1, v2, v4, q1
4300     # will become undefined (such as uninitialized).
4301     tf.Session.reset(target, ["experiment0"])
4302     ```
4303 
4304     Args:
4305       container_name: container name string.
4306 
4307     Returns:
4308       A context manager for defining resource containers for stateful ops,
4309         yields the container name.
4310     """
4311     original_container = self._container
4312     self._container = container_name
4313     try:
4314       yield self._container
4315     finally:
4316       self._container = original_container
4317 
4318   # pylint: enable=g-doc-return-or-yield
4319 
4320   class _ControlDependenciesController(object):
4321     """Context manager for `control_dependencies()`."""
4322 
4323     def __init__(self, graph, control_inputs):
4324       """Create a new `_ControlDependenciesController`.
4325 
4326       A `_ControlDependenciesController` is the context manager for
4327       `with tf.control_dependencies()` blocks.  These normally nest,
4328       as described in the documentation for `control_dependencies()`.
4329 
4330       The `control_inputs` argument list control dependencies that must be
4331       added to the current set of control dependencies.  Because of
4332       uniquification the set can be empty even if the caller passed a list of
4333       ops.  The special value `None` indicates that we want to start a new
4334       empty set of control dependencies instead of extending the current set.
4335 
4336       In that case we also clear the current control flow context, which is an
4337       additional mechanism to add control dependencies.
4338 
4339       Args:
4340         graph: The graph that this controller is managing.
4341         control_inputs: List of ops to use as control inputs in addition
4342           to the current control dependencies.  None to indicate that
4343           the dependencies should be cleared.
4344       """
4345       self._graph = graph
4346       if control_inputs is None:
4347         self._control_inputs_val = []
4348         self._new_stack = True
4349       else:
4350         self._control_inputs_val = control_inputs
4351         self._new_stack = False
4352       self._seen_nodes = set()
4353       self._old_stack = None
4354       self._old_control_flow_context = None
4355 
4356 # pylint: disable=protected-access
4357 
4358     def __enter__(self):
4359       if self._new_stack:
4360         # Clear the control_dependencies graph.
4361         self._old_stack = self._graph._control_dependencies_stack
4362         self._graph._control_dependencies_stack = []
4363         # Clear the control_flow_context too.
4364         self._old_control_flow_context = self._graph._get_control_flow_context()
4365         self._graph._set_control_flow_context(None)
4366       self._graph._push_control_dependencies_controller(self)
4367 
4368     def __exit__(self, unused_type, unused_value, unused_traceback):
4369       self._graph._pop_control_dependencies_controller(self)
4370       if self._new_stack:
4371         self._graph._control_dependencies_stack = self._old_stack
4372         self._graph._set_control_flow_context(self._old_control_flow_context)
4373 
4374 # pylint: enable=protected-access
4375 
4376     @property
4377     def control_inputs(self):
4378       return self._control_inputs_val
4379 
4380     def add_op(self, op):
4381       self._seen_nodes.add(op)
4382 
4383     def op_in_group(self, op):
4384       return op in self._seen_nodes
4385 
4386   def _push_control_dependencies_controller(self, controller):
4387     self._control_dependencies_stack.append(controller)
4388 
4389   def _pop_control_dependencies_controller(self, controller):
4390     assert self._control_dependencies_stack[-1] is controller
4391     self._control_dependencies_stack.pop()
4392 
4393   def _current_control_dependencies(self):
4394     ret = set()
4395     for controller in self._control_dependencies_stack:
4396       for op in controller.control_inputs:
4397         ret.add(op)
4398     return ret
4399 
4400   def _control_dependencies_for_inputs(self, input_ops):
4401     """For an op that takes `input_ops` as inputs, compute control inputs.
4402 
4403     The returned control dependencies should yield an execution that
4404     is equivalent to adding all control inputs in
4405     self._control_dependencies_stack to a newly created op. However,
4406     this function attempts to prune the returned control dependencies
4407     by observing that nodes created within the same `with
4408     control_dependencies(...):` block may have data dependencies that make
4409     the explicit approach redundant.
4410 
4411     Args:
4412       input_ops: The data input ops for an op to be created.
4413 
4414     Returns:
4415       A list of control inputs for the op to be created.
4416     """
4417     ret = []
4418     for controller in self._control_dependencies_stack:
4419       # If any of the input_ops already depends on the inputs from controller,
4420       # we say that the new op is dominated (by that input), and we therefore
4421       # do not need to add control dependencies for this controller's inputs.
4422       dominated = False
4423       for op in input_ops:
4424         if controller.op_in_group(op):
4425           dominated = True
4426           break
4427       if not dominated:
4428         # Don't add a control input if we already have a data dependency on i.
4429         # NOTE(mrry): We do not currently track transitive data dependencies,
4430         #   so we may add redundant control inputs.
4431         ret.extend([c for c in controller.control_inputs if c not in input_ops])
4432     return ret
4433 
4434   def _record_op_seen_by_control_dependencies(self, op):
4435     """Record that the given op depends on all registered control dependencies.
4436 
4437     Args:
4438       op: An Operation.
4439     """
4440     for controller in self._control_dependencies_stack:
4441       controller.add_op(op)
4442 
4443   def control_dependencies(self, control_inputs):
4444     """Returns a context manager that specifies control dependencies.
4445 
4446     Use with the `with` keyword to specify that all operations constructed
4447     within the context should have control dependencies on
4448     `control_inputs`. For example:
4449 
4450     ```python
4451     with g.control_dependencies([a, b, c]):
4452       # `d` and `e` will only run after `a`, `b`, and `c` have executed.
4453       d = ...
4454       e = ...
4455     ```
4456 
4457     Multiple calls to `control_dependencies()` can be nested, and in
4458     that case a new `Operation` will have control dependencies on the union
4459     of `control_inputs` from all active contexts.
4460 
4461     ```python
4462     with g.control_dependencies([a, b]):
4463       # Ops constructed here run after `a` and `b`.
4464       with g.control_dependencies([c, d]):
4465         # Ops constructed here run after `a`, `b`, `c`, and `d`.
4466     ```
4467 
4468     You can pass None to clear the control dependencies:
4469 
4470     ```python
4471     with g.control_dependencies([a, b]):
4472       # Ops constructed here run after `a` and `b`.
4473       with g.control_dependencies(None):
4474         # Ops constructed here run normally, not waiting for either `a` or `b`.
4475         with g.control_dependencies([c, d]):
4476           # Ops constructed here run after `c` and `d`, also not waiting
4477           # for either `a` or `b`.
4478     ```
4479 
4480     *N.B.* The control dependencies context applies *only* to ops that
4481     are constructed within the context. Merely using an op or tensor
4482     in the context does not add a control dependency. The following
4483     example illustrates this point:
4484 
4485     ```python
4486     # WRONG
4487     def my_func(pred, tensor):
4488       t = tf.matmul(tensor, tensor)
4489       with tf.control_dependencies([pred]):
4490         # The matmul op is created outside the context, so no control
4491         # dependency will be added.
4492         return t
4493 
4494     # RIGHT
4495     def my_func(pred, tensor):
4496       with tf.control_dependencies([pred]):
4497         # The matmul op is created in the context, so a control dependency
4498         # will be added.
4499         return tf.matmul(tensor, tensor)
4500     ```
4501 
4502     Also note that though execution of ops created under this scope will trigger
4503     execution of the dependencies, the ops created under this scope might still
4504     be pruned from a normal tensorflow graph. For example, in the following
4505     snippet of code the dependencies are never executed:
4506 
4507     ```python
4508       loss = model.loss()
4509       with tf.control_dependencies(dependencies):
4510         loss = loss + tf.constant(1)  # note: dependencies ignored in the
4511                                       # backward pass
4512       return tf.gradients(loss, model.variables)
4513     ```
4514 
4515     This is because evaluating the gradient graph does not require evaluating
4516     the constant(1) op created in the forward pass.
4517 
4518     Args:
4519       control_inputs: A list of `Operation` or `Tensor` objects which
4520         must be executed or computed before running the operations
4521         defined in the context.  Can also be `None` to clear the control
4522         dependencies.
4523 
4524     Returns:
4525      A context manager that specifies control dependencies for all
4526      operations constructed within the context.
4527 
4528     Raises:
4529       TypeError: If `control_inputs` is not a list of `Operation` or
4530         `Tensor` objects.
4531     """
4532     if control_inputs is None:
4533       return self._ControlDependenciesController(self, None)
4534     # First convert the inputs to ops, and deduplicate them.
4535     # NOTE(mrry): Other than deduplication, we do not currently track direct
4536     #   or indirect dependencies between control_inputs, which may result in
4537     #   redundant control inputs.
4538     control_ops = []
4539     current = self._current_control_dependencies()
4540     for c in control_inputs:
4541       if isinstance(c, IndexedSlices):
4542         c = c.op
4543       c = self.as_graph_element(c)
4544       if isinstance(c, Tensor):
4545         c = c.op
4546       elif not isinstance(c, Operation):
4547         raise TypeError("Control input must be Operation or Tensor: %s" % c)
4548       if c not in current:
4549         control_ops.append(c)
4550         current.add(c)
4551     return self._ControlDependenciesController(self, control_ops)
4552 
4553   # pylint: disable=g-doc-return-or-yield
4554   @tf_contextlib.contextmanager
4555   def _attr_scope(self, attr_map):
4556     """EXPERIMENTAL: A context manager for setting attributes on operators.
4557 
4558     This context manager can be used to add additional
4559     attributes to operators within the scope of the context.
4560 
4561     For example:
4562 
4563        with ops.Graph().as_default() as g:
4564          f_1 = Foo()  # No extra attributes
4565          with g._attr_scope({"_a": tf.attr_value_pb2.AttrValue(b=False)}):
4566            f_2 = Foo()  # Additional attribute _a=False
4567            with g._attr_scope({"_a": tf.attr_value_pb2.AttrValue(b=True)}):
4568              f_3 = Foo()  # Additional attribute _a=False
4569              with g._attr_scope({"_a": None}):
4570                f_4 = Foo()  # No additional attributes.
4571 
4572     Args:
4573       attr_map: A dictionary mapping attr name strings to
4574         AttrValue protocol buffers or None.
4575 
4576     Returns:
4577       A context manager that sets the kernel label to be used for one or more
4578       ops created in that context.
4579 
4580     Raises:
4581       TypeError: If attr_map is not a dictionary mapping
4582         strings to AttrValue protobufs.
4583     """
4584     if not isinstance(attr_map, dict):
4585       raise TypeError("attr_map must be a dictionary mapping "
4586                       "strings to AttrValue protocol buffers")
4587     # The saved_attrs dictionary stores any currently-set labels that
4588     # will be overridden by this context manager.
4589     saved_attrs = {}
4590     # Install the given attribute
4591     for name, attr in attr_map.items():
4592       if not (isinstance(name, six.string_types) and
4593               (isinstance(attr, (type(None), attr_value_pb2.AttrValue)) or
4594                callable(attr))):
4595         raise TypeError("attr_map must be a dictionary mapping "
4596                         "strings to AttrValue protocol buffers or "
4597                         "callables that emit AttrValue protocol buffers")
4598       try:
4599         saved_attrs[name] = self._attr_scope_map[name]
4600       except KeyError:
4601         pass
4602       if attr is None:
4603         del self._attr_scope_map[name]
4604       else:
4605         self._attr_scope_map[name] = attr
4606     try:
4607       yield  # The code within the context runs here.
4608     finally:
4609       # Remove the attributes set for this context, and restore any saved
4610       # attributes.
4611       for name, attr in attr_map.items():
4612         try:
4613           self._attr_scope_map[name] = saved_attrs[name]
4614         except KeyError:
4615           del self._attr_scope_map[name]
4616 
4617   # pylint: enable=g-doc-return-or-yield
4618 
4619   # pylint: disable=g-doc-return-or-yield
4620   @tf_contextlib.contextmanager
4621   def _kernel_label_map(self, op_to_kernel_label_map):
4622     """EXPERIMENTAL: A context manager for setting kernel labels.
4623 
4624     This context manager can be used to select particular
4625     implementations of kernels within the scope of the context.
4626 
4627     For example:
4628 
4629         with ops.Graph().as_default() as g:
4630           f_1 = Foo()  # Uses the default registered kernel for the Foo op.
4631           with g.kernel_label_map({"Foo": "v_2"}):
4632             f_2 = Foo()  # Uses the registered kernel with label "v_2"
4633                          # for the Foo op.
4634             with g.kernel_label_map({"Foo": "v_3"}):
4635               f_3 = Foo()  # Uses the registered kernel with label "v_3"
4636                            # for the Foo op.
4637               with g.kernel_label_map({"Foo": ""}):
4638                 f_4 = Foo()  # Uses the default registered kernel
4639                              # for the Foo op.
4640 
4641     Args:
4642       op_to_kernel_label_map: A dictionary mapping op type strings to
4643         kernel label strings.
4644 
4645     Returns:
4646       A context manager that sets the kernel label to be used for one or more
4647       ops created in that context.
4648 
4649     Raises:
4650       TypeError: If op_to_kernel_label_map is not a dictionary mapping
4651         strings to strings.
4652     """
4653     if not isinstance(op_to_kernel_label_map, dict):
4654       raise TypeError("op_to_kernel_label_map must be a dictionary mapping "
4655                       "strings to strings")
4656     # The saved_labels dictionary stores any currently-set labels that
4657     # will be overridden by this context manager.
4658     saved_labels = {}
4659     # Install the given label
4660     for op_type, label in op_to_kernel_label_map.items():
4661       if not (isinstance(op_type, six.string_types) and
4662               isinstance(label, six.string_types)):
4663         raise TypeError("op_to_kernel_label_map must be a dictionary mapping "
4664                         "strings to strings")
4665       try:
4666         saved_labels[op_type] = self._op_to_kernel_label_map[op_type]
4667       except KeyError:
4668         pass
4669       self._op_to_kernel_label_map[op_type] = label
4670     try:
4671       yield  # The code within the context runs here.
4672     finally:
4673       # Remove the labels set for this context, and restore any saved labels.
4674       for op_type, label in op_to_kernel_label_map.items():
4675         try:
4676           self._op_to_kernel_label_map[op_type] = saved_labels[op_type]
4677         except KeyError:
4678           del self._op_to_kernel_label_map[op_type]
4679 
4680   # pylint: enable=g-doc-return-or-yield
4681 
4682   # pylint: disable=g-doc-return-or-yield
4683   @tf_contextlib.contextmanager
4684   def gradient_override_map(self, op_type_map):
4685     """EXPERIMENTAL: A context manager for overriding gradient functions.
4686 
4687     This context manager can be used to override the gradient function
4688     that will be used for ops within the scope of the context.
4689 
4690     For example:
4691 
4692     ```python
4693     @tf.RegisterGradient("CustomSquare")
4694     def _custom_square_grad(op, grad):
4695       # ...
4696 
4697     with tf.Graph().as_default() as g:
4698       c = tf.constant(5.0)
4699       s_1 = tf.square(c)  # Uses the default gradient for tf.square.
4700       with g.gradient_override_map({"Square": "CustomSquare"}):
4701         s_2 = tf.square(s_2)  # Uses _custom_square_grad to compute the
4702                               # gradient of s_2.
4703     ```
4704 
4705     Args:
4706       op_type_map: A dictionary mapping op type strings to alternative op
4707         type strings.
4708 
4709     Returns:
4710       A context manager that sets the alternative op type to be used for one
4711       or more ops created in that context.
4712 
4713     Raises:
4714       TypeError: If `op_type_map` is not a dictionary mapping strings to
4715         strings.
4716     """
4717     if not isinstance(op_type_map, dict):
4718       raise TypeError("op_type_map must be a dictionary mapping "
4719                       "strings to strings")
4720     # The saved_mappings dictionary stores any currently-set mappings that
4721     # will be overridden by this context manager.
4722     saved_mappings = {}
4723     # Install the given label
4724     for op_type, mapped_op_type in op_type_map.items():
4725       if not (isinstance(op_type, six.string_types) and
4726               isinstance(mapped_op_type, six.string_types)):
4727         raise TypeError("op_type_map must be a dictionary mapping "
4728                         "strings to strings")
4729       try:
4730         saved_mappings[op_type] = self._gradient_override_map[op_type]
4731       except KeyError:
4732         pass
4733       self._gradient_override_map[op_type] = mapped_op_type
4734     try:
4735       yield  # The code within the context runs here.
4736     finally:
4737       # Remove the labels set for this context, and restore any saved labels.
4738       for op_type, mapped_op_type in op_type_map.items():
4739         try:
4740           self._gradient_override_map[op_type] = saved_mappings[op_type]
4741         except KeyError:
4742           del self._gradient_override_map[op_type]
4743

4765   def switch_to_thread_local(self):
4766     """Make device, colocation and dependencies stacks thread-local.
4767 
4768     Device, colocation and dependencies stacks are not thread-local be default.
4769     If multiple threads access them, then the state is shared.  This means that
4770     one thread may affect the behavior of another thread.
4771 
4772     After this method is called, the stacks become thread-local.  If multiple
4773     threads access them, then the state is not shared.  Each thread uses its own
4774     value; a thread doesn't affect other threads by mutating such a stack.
4775 
4776     The initial value for every thread's stack is set to the current value
4777     of the stack when `switch_to_thread_local()` was first called.
4778     """
4779     if not self._stack_state_is_thread_local:
4780       self._stack_state_is_thread_local = True
4781 
4782   @property
4783   def _device_function_stack(self):
4784     if self._stack_state_is_thread_local:
4785       # This may be called from a thread where device_function_stack doesn't yet
4786       # exist.
4787       # pylint: disable=protected-access
4788       if not hasattr(self._thread_local, "_device_function_stack"):
4789         stack_copy_for_this_thread = self._graph_device_function_stack.copy()
4790         self._thread_local._device_function_stack = stack_copy_for_this_thread
4791       return self._thread_local._device_function_stack
4792       # pylint: enable=protected-access
4793     else:
4794       return self._graph_device_function_stack
4795 
4796   @property
4797   def _device_functions_outer_to_inner(self):
4798     user_device_specs = self._device_function_stack.peek_objs()
4799     device_functions = [spec.function for spec in user_device_specs]
4800     device_functions_outer_to_inner = list(reversed(device_functions))
4801     return device_functions_outer_to_inner

4803   def _snapshot_device_function_stack_metadata(self):
4804     """Return device function stack as a list of TraceableObjects.
4805 
4806     Returns:
4807       [traceable_stack.TraceableObject, ...] where each TraceableObject's .obj
4808       member is a displayable name for the user's argument to Graph.device, and
4809       the filename and lineno members point to the code location where
4810       Graph.device was called directly or indirectly by the user.
4811     """
4812     traceable_objects = self._device_function_stack.peek_traceable_objs()
4813     snapshot = []
4814     for obj in traceable_objects:
4815       obj_copy = obj.copy_metadata()
4816       obj_copy.obj = obj.obj.display_name
4817       snapshot.append(obj_copy)
4818     return snapshot

4975 @tf_export("control_dependencies")
4976 def control_dependencies(control_inputs):
4977   """Wrapper for `Graph.control_dependencies()` using the default graph.
4978 
4979   See `tf.Graph.control_dependencies`
4980   for more details.
4981 
4982   When eager execution is enabled, any callable object in the `control_inputs`
4983   list will be called.
4984 
4985   Args:
4986     control_inputs: A list of `Operation` or `Tensor` objects which
4987       must be executed or computed before running the operations
4988       defined in the context.  Can also be `None` to clear the control
4989       dependencies. If eager execution is enabled, any callable object in the
4990       `control_inputs` list will be called.
4991 
4992   Returns:
4993    A context manager that specifies control dependencies for all
4994    operations constructed within the context.
4995   """
4996   if context.executing_eagerly():
4997     if control_inputs:
4998       # Excute any pending callables.
4999       for control in control_inputs:
5000         if callable(control):
5001           control()
5002     return _NullContextmanager()
5003   else:
5004     return get_default_graph().control_dependencies(control_inputs)

5007 class _DefaultStack(threading.local):
5008   """A thread-local stack of objects for providing implicit defaults."""
5009 
5010   def __init__(self):
5011     super(_DefaultStack, self).__init__()
5012     self._enforce_nesting = True
5013     self.stack = []
5014 
5015   def get_default(self):
5016     return self.stack[-1] if len(self.stack) >= 1 else None
5017 
5018   def reset(self):
5019     self.stack = []
5020 
5021   def is_cleared(self):
5022     return not self.stack
5023 
5024   @property
5025   def enforce_nesting(self):
5026     return self._enforce_nesting
5027 
5028   @enforce_nesting.setter
5029   def enforce_nesting(self, value):
5030     self._enforce_nesting = value
5031 
5032   @tf_contextlib.contextmanager
5033   def get_controller(self, default):
5034     """A context manager for manipulating a default stack."""
5035     self.stack.append(default)
5036     try:
5037       yield default
5038     finally:
5039       # stack may be empty if reset() was called
5040       if self.stack:
5041         if self._enforce_nesting:
5042           if self.stack[-1] is not default:
5043             raise AssertionError(
5044                 "Nesting violated for default stack of %s objects" %
5045                 type(default))
5046           self.stack.pop()
5047         else:
5048           self.stack.remove(default)
5049

5051 _default_session_stack = _DefaultStack()  # pylint: disable=protected-access

5053 
5054 def default_session(session):
5055   """Python "with" handler for defining a default session.
5056 
5057   This function provides a means of registering a session for handling
5058   Tensor.eval() and Operation.run() calls. It is primarily intended for use
5059   by session.Session, but can be used with any object that implements
5060   the Session.run() interface.
5061 
5062   Use with the "with" keyword to specify that Tensor.eval() and Operation.run()
5063   invocations within the scope of a block should be executed by a particular
5064   session.
5065 
5066   The default session applies to the current thread only, so it is always
5067   possible to inspect the call stack and determine the scope of a default
5068   session. If you create a new thread, and wish to use the default session
5069   in that thread, you must explicitly add a "with ops.default_session(sess):"
5070   block in that thread's function.
5071 
5072   Example:
5073     The following code examples are equivalent:
5074 
5075     # 1. Using the Session object directly:
5076     sess = ...
5077     c = tf.constant(5.0)
5078     sess.run(c)
5079 
5080     # 2. Using default_session():
5081     sess = ...
5082     with ops.default_session(sess):
5083       c = tf.constant(5.0)
5084       result = c.eval()
5085 
5086     # 3. Overriding default_session():
5087     sess = ...
5088     with ops.default_session(sess):
5089       c = tf.constant(5.0)
5090       with ops.default_session(...):
5091         c.eval(session=sess)
5092 
5093   Args:
5094     session: The session to be installed as the default session.
5095 
5096   Returns:
5097     A context manager for the default session.
5098   """
5099   return _default_session_stack.get_controller(session)
5100 
5101 
5102 @tf_export("get_default_session")
5103 def get_default_session():
5104   """Returns the default session for the current thread.
5105 
5106   The returned `Session` will be the innermost session on which a
5107   `Session` or `Session.as_default()` context has been entered.
5108 
5109   NOTE: The default session is a property of the current thread. If you
5110   create a new thread, and wish to use the default session in that
5111   thread, you must explicitly add a `with sess.as_default():` in that
5112   thread's function.
5113 
5114   Returns:
5115     The default `Session` being used in the current thread.
5116   """
5117   return _default_session_stack.get_default()

5120 def _eval_using_default_session(tensors, feed_dict, graph, session=None):
5121   """Uses the default session to evaluate one or more tensors.
5122 
5123   Args:
5124     tensors: A single Tensor, or a list of Tensor objects.
5125     feed_dict: A dictionary that maps Tensor objects (or tensor names) to lists,
5126       numpy ndarrays, TensorProtos, or strings.
5127     graph: The graph in which the tensors are defined.
5128     session: (Optional) A different session to use to evaluate "tensors".
5129 
5130   Returns:
5131     Either a single numpy ndarray if "tensors" is a single tensor; or a list
5132     of numpy ndarrays that each correspond to the respective element in
5133     "tensors".
5134 
5135   Raises:
5136     ValueError: If no default session is available; the default session
5137       does not have "graph" as its graph; or if "session" is specified,
5138       and it does not have "graph" as its graph.
5139   """
5140   if session is None:
5141     session = get_default_session()
5142     if session is None:
5143       raise ValueError("Cannot evaluate tensor using `eval()`: No default "
5144                        "session is registered. Use `with "
5145                        "sess.as_default()` or pass an explicit session to "
5146                        "`eval(session=sess)`")
5147     if session.graph is not graph:
5148       raise ValueError("Cannot use the default session to evaluate tensor: "
5149                        "the tensor's graph is different from the session's "
5150                        "graph. Pass an explicit session to "
5151                        "`eval(session=sess)`.")
5152   else:
5153     if session.graph is not graph:
5154       raise ValueError("Cannot use the given session to evaluate tensor: "
5155                        "the tensor's graph is different from the session's "
5156                        "graph.")
5157   return session.run(tensors, feed_dict)
5158

5160 def _run_using_default_session(operation, feed_dict, graph, session=None):
5161   """Uses the default session to run "operation".
5162 
5163   Args:
5164     operation: The Operation to be run.
5165     feed_dict: A dictionary that maps Tensor objects (or tensor names) to lists,
5166       numpy ndarrays, TensorProtos, or strings.
5167     graph: The graph in which "operation" is defined.
5168     session: (Optional) A different session to use to run "operation".
5169 
5170   Raises:
5171     ValueError: If no default session is available; the default session
5172       does not have "graph" as its graph; or if "session" is specified,
5173       and it does not have "graph" as its graph.
5174   """
5175   if session is None:
5176     session = get_default_session()
5177     if session is None:
5178       raise ValueError("Cannot execute operation using `run()`: No default "
5179                        "session is registered. Use `with "
5180                        "sess.as_default():` or pass an explicit session to "
5181                        "`run(session=sess)`")
5182     if session.graph is not graph:
5183       raise ValueError("Cannot use the default session to execute operation: "
5184                        "the operation's graph is different from the "
5185                        "session's graph. Pass an explicit session to "
5186                        "run(session=sess).")
5187   else:
5188     if session.graph is not graph:
5189       raise ValueError("Cannot use the given session to execute operation: "
5190                        "the operation's graph is different from the session's "
5191                        "graph.")
5192   session.run(operation, feed_dict)

5195 class _DefaultGraphStack(_DefaultStack):  # pylint: disable=protected-access
5196   """A thread-local stack of objects for providing an implicit default graph."""
5197 
5198   def __init__(self):
5199     super(_DefaultGraphStack, self).__init__()
5200     self._global_default_graph = None
5201 
5202   def get_default(self):
5203     """Override that returns a global default if the stack is empty."""
5204     ret = super(_DefaultGraphStack, self).get_default()
5205     if ret is None:
5206       ret = self._GetGlobalDefaultGraph()
5207     return ret
5208 
5209   def _GetGlobalDefaultGraph(self):
5210     if self._global_default_graph is None:
5211       # TODO(mrry): Perhaps log that the default graph is being used, or set
5212       #   provide some other feedback to prevent confusion when a mixture of
5213       #   the global default graph and an explicit graph are combined in the
5214       #   same process.
5215       self._global_default_graph = Graph()
5216     return self._global_default_graph
5217 
5218   def reset(self):
5219     super(_DefaultGraphStack, self).reset()
5220     self._global_default_graph = None
5221 
5222   @tf_contextlib.contextmanager
5223   def get_controller(self, default):
5224     context.context().context_switches.push(
5225         default.building_function, default.as_default)
5226     try:
5227       with super(_DefaultGraphStack, self).get_controller(
5228           default) as g, context.graph_mode():
5229         yield g
5230     finally:
5231       # If an exception is raised here it may be hiding a related exception in
5232       # the try-block (just above).
5233       context.context().context_switches.pop()
5234

5239 # pylint: disable=g-doc-return-or-yield,line-too-long
5240 @tf_export("init_scope")
5241 @tf_contextlib.contextmanager
5242 def init_scope():
5243   """A context manager that lifts ops out of control-flow scopes and function-building graphs.
5244 
5245   There is often a need to lift variable initialization ops out of control-flow
5246   scopes, function-building graphs, and gradient tapes. Entering an
5247   `init_scope` is a mechanism for satisfying these desiderata. In particular,
5248   entering an `init_scope` has three effects:
5249 
5250     (1) All control dependencies are cleared the moment the scope is entered;
5251         this is equivalent to entering the context manager returned from
5252         `control_dependencies(None)`, which has the side-effect of exiting
5253         control-flow scopes like `tf.cond` and `tf.while_loop`.
5254 
5255     (2) All operations that are created while the scope is active are lifted
5256         into the lowest context on the `context_stack` that is not building a
5257         graph function. Here, a context is defined as either a graph or an eager
5258         context. Every context switch, i.e., every installation of a graph as
5259         the default graph and every switch into eager mode, is logged in a
5260         thread-local stack called `context_switches`; the log entry for a
5261         context switch is popped from the stack when the context is exited.
5262         Entering an `init_scope` is equivalent to crawling up
5263         `context_switches`, finding the first context that is not building a
5264         graph function, and entering it. A caveat is that if graph mode is
5265         enabled but the default graph stack is empty, then entering an
5266         `init_scope` will simply install a fresh graph as the default one.
5267 
5268     (3) The gradient tape is paused while the scope is active.
5269 
5270   When eager execution is enabled, code inside an init_scope block runs with
5271   eager execution enabled even when defining graph functions via
5272   tf.contrib.eager.defun. For example:
5273 
5274   ```python
5275   tf.enable_eager_execution()
5276 
5277   @tf.contrib.eager.defun
5278   def func():
5279     # A defun-decorated function constructs TensorFlow graphs,
5280     # it does not execute eagerly.
5281     assert not tf.executing_eagerly()
5282     with tf.init_scope():
5283       # Initialization runs with eager execution enabled
5284       assert tf.executing_eagerly()
5285   ```
5286 
5287   Raises:
5288     RuntimeError: if graph state is incompatible with this initialization.
5289   """
5290   # pylint: enable=g-doc-return-or-yield,line-too-long
5291 
5292   if context.executing_eagerly():
5293     # Fastpath.
5294     with tape.stop_recording():
5295       yield
5296   else:
5297     # Retrieve the active name scope: entering an `init_scope` preserves
5298     # the name scope of the current context.
5299     default_graph = get_default_graph()
5300     scope = default_graph.get_name_scope()
5301     if scope and scope[-1] != "/":
5302       # Names that end with trailing slashes are treated by `name_scope` as
5303       # absolute.
5304       scope = scope + "/"
5305     inner_device_stack = default_graph._device_function_stack  # pylint: disable=protected-access
5306 
5307     outer_context = None
5308     if not _default_graph_stack.stack:
5309       # If the default graph stack is empty, then we cannot be building a
5310       # function. Install the global graph (which, in this case, is also the
5311       # default graph) as the outer context.
5312       if default_graph.building_function:
5313         raise RuntimeError("The global graph is building a function.")
5314       outer_context = default_graph.as_default
5315     else:
5316       # Find a context that is not building a function.
5317       for stack_entry in reversed(context.context().context_switches.stack):
5318         if not stack_entry.is_building_function:
5319           outer_context = stack_entry.enter_context_fn
5320           break
5321 
5322       if outer_context is None:
5323         # As a last resort, obtain the global default graph; this graph doesn't
5324         # necessarily live on the graph stack (and hence it doesn't necessarily
5325         # live on the context stack), but it is stored in the graph stack's
5326         # encapsulating object.
5327         outer_context = _default_graph_stack._GetGlobalDefaultGraph().as_default  # pylint: disable=protected-access
5328 
5329     if outer_context is None:
5330       # Sanity check; this shouldn't be triggered.
5331       raise RuntimeError("All graphs are building functions, and no "
5332                          "eager context was previously active.")
5333 
5334     outer_graph = None
5335     outer_device_stack = None
5336     try:
5337       with outer_context(), name_scope(scope), control_dependencies(
5338           None), tape.stop_recording():
5339         if not context.executing_eagerly():
5340           # The device stack is preserved when lifting into a graph. Eager
5341           # execution doesn't implement device stacks and in particular it
5342           # doesn't support device functions, so in general it's not possible
5343           # to do the same when lifting into the eager context.
5344           outer_graph = get_default_graph()
5345           outer_device_stack = outer_graph._device_function_stack  # pylint: disable=protected-access
5346           outer_graph._device_function_stack = inner_device_stack  # pylint: disable=protected-access
5347         yield
5348     finally:
5349       # If an exception is raised here it may be hiding a related exception in
5350       # try-block (just above).
5351       if outer_graph is not None:
5352         outer_graph._device_function_stack = outer_device_stack  # pylint: disable=protected-access
5353 
5354 
5355 @tf_export("enable_eager_execution")
5356 def enable_eager_execution(config=None,
5357                            device_policy=None,
5358                            execution_mode=None):
5359   """Enables eager execution for the lifetime of this program.
5360 
5361   Eager execution provides an imperative interface to TensorFlow. With eager
5362   execution enabled, TensorFlow functions execute operations immediately (as
5363   opposed to adding to a graph to be executed later in a `tf.Session`) and
5364   return concrete values (as opposed to symbolic references to a node in a
5365   computational graph).
5366 
5367   For example:
5368 
5369   ```python
5370   tf.enable_eager_execution()
5371 
5372   # After eager execution is enabled, operations are executed as they are
5373   # defined and Tensor objects hold concrete values, which can be accessed as
5374   # numpy.ndarray`s through the numpy() method.
5375   assert tf.multiply(6, 7).numpy() == 42
5376   ```
5377 
5378   Eager execution cannot be enabled after TensorFlow APIs have been used to
5379   create or execute graphs. It is typically recommended to invoke this function
5380   at program startup and not in a library (as most libraries should be usable
5381   both with and without eager execution).
5382 
5383   Args:
5384     config: (Optional.) A `tf.ConfigProto` to use to configure the environment
5385       in which operations are executed. Note that `tf.ConfigProto` is also
5386       used to configure graph execution (via `tf.Session`) and many options
5387       within `tf.ConfigProto` are not implemented (or are irrelevant) when
5388       eager execution is enabled.
5389     device_policy: (Optional.) Policy controlling how operations requiring
5390       inputs on a specific device (e.g., a GPU 0) handle inputs on a different
5391       device  (e.g. GPU 1 or CPU). When set to None, an appropriate value will be
5392       picked automatically. The value picked may change between TensorFlow
5393       releases.
5394       Valid values:
5395       - tf.contrib.eager.DEVICE_PLACEMENT_EXPLICIT: raises an error if the
5396         placement is not correct.
5397       - tf.contrib.eager.DEVICE_PLACEMENT_WARN: copies the tensors which are not
5398         on the right device but logs a warning.
5399       - tf.contrib.eager.DEVICE_PLACEMENT_SILENT: silently copies the tensors.
5400         Note that this may hide performance problems as there is no notification
5401         provided when operations are blocked on the tensor being copied between
5402         devices.
5403       - tf.contrib.eager.DEVICE_PLACEMENT_SILENT_FOR_INT32: silently copies
5404         int32 tensors, raising errors on the other ones.
5405     execution_mode: (Optional.) Policy controlling how operations dispatched are
5406       actually executed. When set to None, an appropriate value will be picked
5407       automatically. The value picked may change between TensorFlow releases.
5408       Valid values:
5409       - tf.contrib.eager.SYNC: executes each operation synchronously.
5410       - tf.contrib.eager.ASYNC: executes each operation asynchronously. These
5411         operations may return "non-ready" handles.
5412 
5413   Raises:
5414     ValueError: If eager execution is enabled after creating/executing a
5415      TensorFlow graph, or if options provided conflict with a previous call
5416      to this function.
5417   """
5418   if context.default_execution_mode != context.EAGER_MODE:
5419     return enable_eager_execution_internal(
5420         config=config,
5421         device_policy=device_policy,
5422         execution_mode=execution_mode,
5423         server_def=None)
5424 
5425 
5426 def enable_eager_execution_internal(config=None,
5427                                     device_policy=None,
5428                                     execution_mode=None,
5429                                     server_def=None):
5430   """Enables eager execution for the lifetime of this program.
5431 
5432   Most of the doc string for enable_eager_execution is relevant here as well.
5433   Args:
5434     config: See enable_eager_execution doc string
5435     device_policy: See enable_eager_execution doc string
5436     execution_mode: See enable_eager_execution doc string
5437     server_def: (Optional.) A tensorflow::ServerDef proto.
5438       Enables execution on remote devices. GrpcServers need to be started by
5439       creating an identical server_def to this, and setting the appropriate
5440       task_indexes, so that the servers can communicate. It will then be
5441       possible to execute operations on remote devices.
5442 
5443   Raises:
5444     ValueError
5445 
5446   """
5447   if config is not None and not isinstance(config, config_pb2.ConfigProto):
5448     raise TypeError(
5449         "config must be a tf.ConfigProto, but got %s" % type(config))
5450   if device_policy not in (None, context.DEVICE_PLACEMENT_EXPLICIT,
5451                            context.DEVICE_PLACEMENT_WARN,
5452                            context.DEVICE_PLACEMENT_SILENT,
5453                            context.DEVICE_PLACEMENT_SILENT_FOR_INT32):
5454     raise ValueError(
5455         "device_policy must be one of None, tf.contrib.eager.DEVICE_PLACEMENT_*"
5456     )
5457   if execution_mode not in (None, context.SYNC, context.ASYNC):
5458     raise ValueError(
5459         "execution_mode must be one of None, tf.contrib.eager.SYNC, "
5460         "tf.contrib.eager.ASYNC")
5461   if context.default_execution_mode == context.GRAPH_MODE:
5462     graph_mode_has_been_used = (
5463         _default_session_stack.stack
5464         or len(get_default_graph().get_operations()) > 0)  # pylint: disable=g-explicit-length-test
5465     if graph_mode_has_been_used:
5466       raise ValueError(
5467           "tf.enable_eager_execution must be called at program startup.")
5468   context.default_execution_mode = context.EAGER_MODE
5469   # pylint: disable=protected-access
5470   if context._context is None:
5471     context._context = context.Context(
5472         config=config,
5473         device_policy=device_policy,
5474         execution_mode=execution_mode,
5475         server_def=server_def)
5476   elif ((config is not None and config is not context._context._config) or
5477         (device_policy is not None and
5478          device_policy is not context._context._device_policy) or
5479         (execution_mode is not None and
5480          execution_mode is not context._context._execution_mode)):
5481     raise ValueError("Trying to change the options of an active eager"
5482                      " execution. Context config: %s, specified config:"
5483                      " %s. Context device policy: %s, specified device"
5484                      " policy: %s. Context execution mode: %s, "
5485                      " specified execution mode %s." %
5486                      (context._context._config, config,
5487                       context._context._device_policy, device_policy,
5488                       context._context._execution_mode, execution_mode))
5489   else:
5490     raise ValueError(
5491         "tf.enable_eager_execution must be called at program startup.")
5492 
5493   # Monkey patch to get rid of an unnecessary conditional since the context is
5494   # now initialized.
5495   context.context = context.context_safe
5496 
5497 
5498 def eager_run(main=None, argv=None):
5499   """Runs the program with an optional main function and argv list.
5500 
5501   The program will run with eager execution enabled.
5502 
5503   Example:
5504   ```python
5505   import tensorflow as tf
5506   # Import subject to future changes:
5507   from tensorflow.contrib.eager.python import tfe
5508 
5509   def main(_):
5510     u = tf.constant(6.0)
5511     v = tf.constant(7.0)
5512     print(u * v)
5513 
5514   if __name__ == "__main__":
5515     tfe.run()
5516   ```
5517 
5518   Args:
5519     main: the main function to run.
5520     argv: the arguments to pass to it.
5521   """
5522   enable_eager_execution()
5523   app.run(main, argv)
5524

5526 @tf_export("reset_default_graph")
5527 def reset_default_graph():
5528   """Clears the default graph stack and resets the global default graph.
5529 
5530   NOTE: The default graph is a property of the current thread. This
5531   function applies only to the current thread.  Calling this function while
5532   a `tf.Session` or `tf.InteractiveSession` is active will result in undefined
5533   behavior. Using any previously created `tf.Operation` or `tf.Tensor` objects
5534   after calling this function will result in undefined behavior.
5535   Raises:
5536     AssertionError: If this function is called within a nested graph.
5537   """
5538   if not _default_graph_stack.is_cleared():
5539     raise AssertionError("Do not use tf.reset_default_graph() to clear "
5540                          "nested graphs. If you need a cleared graph, "
5541                          "exit the nesting and create a new graph.")
5542   _default_graph_stack.reset()
5543

5545 @tf_export("get_default_graph")
5546 def get_default_graph():
5547   """Returns the default graph for the current thread.
5548 
5549   The returned graph will be the innermost graph on which a
5550   `Graph.as_default()` context has been entered, or a global default
5551   graph if none has been explicitly created.
5552 
5553   NOTE: The default graph is a property of the current thread. If you
5554   create a new thread, and wish to use the default graph in that
5555   thread, you must explicitly add a `with g.as_default():` in that
5556   thread's function.
5557 
5558   Returns:
5559     The default `Graph` being used in the current thread.
5560   """
5561   return _default_graph_stack.get_default()
5562 
5563 def has_default_graph():
5564   """Returns True if there is a default graph."""
5565   return len(_default_graph_stack.stack) >= 1

5568 def get_name_scope():
5569   """Returns the current name scope in the default_graph.
5570 
5571   For example:
5572 
5573   ```python
5574   with tf.name_scope('scope1'):
5575     with tf.name_scope('scope2'):
5576       print(tf.get_name_scope())
5577   ```
5578   would print the string `scope1/scope2`.
5579 
5580   Returns:
5581     A string representing the current name scope.
5582   """
5583   if context.executing_eagerly():
5584     return context.context().scope_name.rstrip("/")
5585   return get_default_graph().get_name_scope()

5588 def _assert_same_graph(original_item, item):
5589   """Fail if the 2 items are from different graphs.
5590 
5591   Args:
5592     original_item: Original item to check against.
5593     item: Item to check.
5594 
5595   Raises:
5596     ValueError: if graphs do not match.
5597   """
5598   if original_item.graph is not item.graph:
5599     raise ValueError("%s must be from the same graph as %s." % (item,
5600                                                                 original_item))

5602 
5603 def _get_graph_from_inputs(op_input_list, graph=None):
5604   """Returns the appropriate graph to use for the given inputs.
5605 
5606   This library method provides a consistent algorithm for choosing the graph
5607   in which an Operation should be constructed:
5608 
5609   1. If the default graph is being used to construct a function, we
5610      use the default graph.
5611   2. If the "graph" is specified explicitly, we validate that all of the inputs
5612      in "op_input_list" are compatible with that graph.
5613   3. Otherwise, we attempt to select a graph from the first Operation-
5614      or Tensor-valued input in "op_input_list", and validate that all other
5615      such inputs are in the same graph.
5616   4. If the graph was not specified and it could not be inferred from
5617      "op_input_list", we attempt to use the default graph.
5618 
5619   Args:
5620     op_input_list: A list of inputs to an operation, which may include `Tensor`,
5621       `Operation`, and other objects that may be converted to a graph element.
5622     graph: (Optional) The explicit graph to use.
5623 
5624   Raises:
5625     TypeError: If op_input_list is not a list or tuple, or if graph is not a
5626       Graph.
5627     ValueError: If a graph is explicitly passed and not all inputs are from it,
5628       or if the inputs are from multiple graphs, or we could not find a graph
5629       and there was no default graph.
5630 
5631   Returns:
5632     The appropriate graph to use for the given inputs.
5633 
5634   """
5635   if get_default_graph().building_function:
5636     return get_default_graph()
5637 
5638   op_input_list = tuple(op_input_list)  # Handle generators correctly
5639   if graph and not isinstance(graph, Graph):
5640     raise TypeError("Input graph needs to be a Graph: %s" % graph)
5641 
5642   # 1. We validate that all of the inputs are from the same graph. This is
5643   #    either the supplied graph parameter, or the first one selected from one
5644   #    the graph-element-valued inputs. In the latter case, we hold onto
5645   #    that input in original_graph_element so we can provide a more
5646   #    informative error if a mismatch is found.
5647   original_graph_element = None
5648   for op_input in op_input_list:
5649     # Determine if this is a valid graph_element.
5650     # TODO(josh11b): Note that we exclude subclasses of Tensor. Need to clean this
5651     # up.
5652     graph_element = None
5653     if (isinstance(op_input, (Operation, _TensorLike)) and
5654         ((not isinstance(op_input, Tensor)) or type(op_input) == Tensor)):  # pylint: disable=unidiomatic-typecheck
5655       graph_element = op_input
5656     else:
5657       graph_element = _as_graph_element(op_input)
5658 
5659     if graph_element is not None:
5660       if not graph:
5661         original_graph_element = graph_element
5662         graph = graph_element.graph
5663       elif original_graph_element is not None:
5664         _assert_same_graph(original_graph_element, graph_element)
5665       elif graph_element.graph is not graph:
5666         raise ValueError("%s is not from the passed-in graph." % graph_element)
5667 
5668   # 2. If all else fails, we use the default graph, which is always there.
5669   return graph or get_default_graph()
5670 
5671 
5672 @tf_export("GraphKeys")
5673 class GraphKeys(object):
5674   """Standard names to use for graph collections.
5675 
5676   The standard library uses various well-known names to collect and
5677   retrieve values associated with a graph. For example, the
5678   `tf.Optimizer` subclasses default to optimizing the variables
5679   collected under `tf.GraphKeys.TRAINABLE_VARIABLES` if none is
5680   specified, but it is also possible to pass an explicit list of
5681   variables.
5682 
5683   The following standard keys are defined:
5684 
5685   * `GLOBAL_VARIABLES`: the default collection of `Variable` objects, shared
5686     across distributed environment (model variables are subset of these). See
5687     `tf.global_variables`
5688     for more details.
5689     Commonly, all `TRAINABLE_VARIABLES` variables will be in `MODEL_VARIABLES`,
5690     and all `MODEL_VARIABLES` variables will be in `GLOBAL_VARIABLES`.
5691   * `LOCAL_VARIABLES`: the subset of `Variable` objects that are local to each
5692     machine. Usually used for temporarily variables, like counters.
5693     Note: use `tf.contrib.framework.local_variable` to add to this collection.
5694   * `MODEL_VARIABLES`: the subset of `Variable` objects that are used in the
5695     model for inference (feed forward). Note: use
5696     `tf.contrib.framework.model_variable` to add to this collection.
5697   * `TRAINABLE_VARIABLES`: the subset of `Variable` objects that will
5698     be trained by an optimizer. See
5699     `tf.trainable_variables`
5700     for more details.
5701   * `SUMMARIES`: the summary `Tensor` objects that have been created in the
5702     graph. See
5703     `tf.summary.merge_all`
5704     for more details.
5705   * `QUEUE_RUNNERS`: the `QueueRunner` objects that are used to
5706     produce input for a computation. See
5707     `tf.train.start_queue_runners`
5708     for more details.
5709   * `MOVING_AVERAGE_VARIABLES`: the subset of `Variable` objects that will also
5710     keep moving averages.  See
5711     `tf.moving_average_variables`
5712     for more details.
5713   * `REGULARIZATION_LOSSES`: regularization losses collected during graph
5714     construction.
5715 
5716   The following standard keys are _defined_, but their collections are **not**
5717   automatically populated as many of the others are:
5718 
5719   * `WEIGHTS`
5720   * `BIASES`
5721   * `ACTIVATIONS`
5722   """
5723 
5724   # Key to collect Variable objects that are global (shared across machines).
5725   # Default collection for all variables, except local ones.
5726   GLOBAL_VARIABLES = "variables"
5727   # Key to collect local variables that are local to the machine and are not
5728   # saved/restored.
5729   LOCAL_VARIABLES = "local_variables"
5730   # Key to collect local variables which are used to accumulate interal state
5731   # to be used in tf.metrics.*.
5732   METRIC_VARIABLES = "metric_variables"
5733   # Key to collect model variables defined by layers.
5734   MODEL_VARIABLES = "model_variables"
5735   # Key to collect Variable objects that will be trained by the
5736   # optimizers.
5737   TRAINABLE_VARIABLES = "trainable_variables"
5738   # Key to collect summaries.
5739   SUMMARIES = "summaries"
5740   # Key to collect QueueRunners.
5741   QUEUE_RUNNERS = "queue_runners"
5742   # Key to collect table initializers.
5743   TABLE_INITIALIZERS = "table_initializer"
5744   # Key to collect asset filepaths. An asset represents an external resource
5745   # like a vocabulary file.
5746   ASSET_FILEPATHS = "asset_filepaths"
5747   # Key to collect Variable objects that keep moving averages.
5748   MOVING_AVERAGE_VARIABLES = "moving_average_variables"
5749   # Key to collect regularization losses at graph construction.
5750   REGULARIZATION_LOSSES = "regularization_losses"
5751   # Key to collect concatenated sharded variables.
5752   CONCATENATED_VARIABLES = "concatenated_variables"
5753   # Key to collect savers.
5754   SAVERS = "savers"
5755   # Key to collect weights
5756   WEIGHTS = "weights"
5757   # Key to collect biases
5758   BIASES = "biases"
5759   # Key to collect activations
5760   ACTIVATIONS = "activations"
5761   # Key to collect update_ops
5762   UPDATE_OPS = "update_ops"
5763   # Key to collect losses
5764   LOSSES = "losses"
5765   # Key to collect BaseSaverBuilder.SaveableObject instances for checkpointing.
5766   SAVEABLE_OBJECTS = "saveable_objects"
5767   # Key to collect all shared resources used by the graph which need to be
5768   # initialized once per cluster.
5769   RESOURCES = "resources"
5770   # Key to collect all shared resources used in this graph which need to be
5771   # initialized once per session.
5772   LOCAL_RESOURCES = "local_resources"
5773   # Trainable resource-style variables.
5774   TRAINABLE_RESOURCE_VARIABLES = "trainable_resource_variables"
5775 
5776   # Key to indicate various ops.
5777   INIT_OP = "init_op"
5778   LOCAL_INIT_OP = "local_init_op"
5779   READY_OP = "ready_op"
5780   READY_FOR_LOCAL_INIT_OP = "ready_for_local_init_op"
5781   SUMMARY_OP = "summary_op"
5782   GLOBAL_STEP = "global_step"
5783 
5784   # Used to count the number of evaluations performed during a single evaluation
5785   # run.
5786   EVAL_STEP = "eval_step"
5787   TRAIN_OP = "train_op"
5788 
5789   # Key for control flow context.
5790   COND_CONTEXT = "cond_context"
5791   WHILE_CONTEXT = "while_context"
5792 
5793   # Used to store v2 summary names.
5794   _SUMMARY_COLLECTION = "_SUMMARY_V2"
5795 
5796   # List of all collections that keep track of variables.
5797   _VARIABLE_COLLECTIONS = [
5798       GLOBAL_VARIABLES,
5799       LOCAL_VARIABLES,
5800       METRIC_VARIABLES,
5801       MODEL_VARIABLES,
5802       TRAINABLE_VARIABLES,
5803       MOVING_AVERAGE_VARIABLES,
5804       CONCATENATED_VARIABLES,
5805       TRAINABLE_RESOURCE_VARIABLES,
5806   ]
5807 
5808   # Key for streaming model ports.
5809   # NOTE(yuanbyu): internal and experimental.
5810   _STREAMING_MODEL_PORTS = "streaming_model_ports"
5811 
5812   @decorator_utils.classproperty
5813   @deprecation.deprecated(None, "Use `tf.GraphKeys.GLOBAL_VARIABLES` instead.")
5814   def VARIABLES(cls):  # pylint: disable=no-self-argument
5815     return cls.GLOBAL_VARIABLES
5816 
5817 
5818 def dismantle_graph(graph):
5819   """Cleans up reference cycles from a `Graph`.
5820 
5821   Helpful for making sure the garbage collector doesn't need to run after a
5822   temporary `Graph` is no longer needed.
5823 
5824   Args:
5825     graph: A `Graph` object to destroy. Neither it nor any of its ops are usable
5826       after this function runs.
5827   """
5828   memory.dismantle_ordered_dict(graph._functions)  # pylint: disable=protected-access
5829 
5830   # Now clean up Operation<->Graph reference cycles by clearing all of the
5831   # attributes for the Graph and its ops.
5832   graph_operations = graph.get_operations()
5833   for op in graph_operations:
5834     op.__dict__ = {}
5835   graph.__dict__ = {}

5838 @tf_export("add_to_collection")
5839 def add_to_collection(name, value):
5840   """Wrapper for `Graph.add_to_collection()` using the default graph.
5841 
5842   See `tf.Graph.add_to_collection`
5843   for more details.
5844 
5845   Args:
5846     name: The key for the collection. For example, the `GraphKeys` class
5847       contains many standard names for collections.
5848     value: The value to add to the collection.
5849 
5850   @compatibility(eager)
5851   Collections are only supported in eager when variables are created inside an
5852   EagerVariableStore (e.g. as part of a layer or template).
5853   @end_compatibility
5854   """
5855   get_default_graph().add_to_collection(name, value)

5857 @tf_export("add_to_collections")
5858 def add_to_collections(names, value):
5859   """Wrapper for `Graph.add_to_collections()` using the default graph.
5860 
5861   See `tf.Graph.add_to_collections`
5862   for more details.
5863 
5864   Args:
5865     names: The key for the collections. The `GraphKeys` class
5866       contains many standard names for collections.
5867     value: The value to add to the collections.
5868 
5869   @compatibility(eager)
5870   Collections are only supported in eager when variables are created inside an
5871   EagerVariableStore (e.g. as part of a layer or template).
5872   @end_compatibility
5873   """
5874   get_default_graph().add_to_collections(names, value)

5901 @tf_export("get_collection")
5902 def get_collection(key, scope=None):
5903   """Wrapper for `Graph.get_collection()` using the default graph.
5904 
5905   See `tf.Graph.get_collection`
5906   for more details.
5907 
5908   Args:
5909     key: The key for the collection. For example, the `GraphKeys` class
5910       contains many standard names for collections.
5911     scope: (Optional.) If supplied, the resulting list is filtered to include
5912       only items whose `name` attribute matches using `re.match`. Items
5913       without a `name` attribute are never returned if a scope is supplied and
5914       the choice or `re.match` means that a `scope` without special tokens
5915       filters by prefix.
5916 
5917   Returns:
5918     The list of values in the collection with the given `name`, or
5919     an empty list if no value has been added to that collection. The
5920     list contains the values in the order under which they were
5921     collected.
5922 
5923   @compatibility(eager)
5924   Collections are not supported when eager execution is enabled.
5925   @end_compatibility
5926   """
5927   return get_default_graph().get_collection(key, scope)
